WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African-American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:15.000
Today, of the Southern World History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill,

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:22.000
I am in New Orleans, Louisiana, to film an interview for the Civil Rights History Project,

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:30.000
which is a joint undertaking of the Library of Congress, the Smithsonian's National Museum of African-American History and Culture,

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:37.000
our videographer is John Bishop, and Missy Lane Nichols, the project curator from the museum,

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:44.000
is here today with us in New Orleans. We are in the home of Mr. Richard and Mrs. Anne Sobel,

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:53.000
and are here for an interview to touch on Mr. Sobel's curves and turning in some connection to the Tbubbuluza.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:59.000
And I think that's the quick step. So Mr. Sobel, thank you so much for welcoming us.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:01.000
We're glad to have you here.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:12.000
So when you started, I could just have you give a basic sketch of your childhood family and upbringing in New York City.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:20.000
I grew up in New York City. I lived on the west side of Manhattan. My father was a lawyer. My mother was a mathematics teacher

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:25.000
and one of the high schools in New York.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:32.000
I went through schools in New York. I went to the Bronx High School of Science, and I went to college,

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:39.000
a union college, and was connected in New York, and came back to New York to go to Columbia Law School.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:42.000
Always had so many to spend at your school?

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:52.000
My father was a lawyer, and I was, it was explained to me earlier on that I was going to be a lawyer, and I accepted that.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:02:03.000
Did you, did civil rights come into your kind of active attention as you were visiting with the Law Review while at Columbia?

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:17.000
I wrote something about the Jerry Mander decision of the Supreme Court in Alabama while I was in law school,

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:29.000
which was published. But really the truth is that for the most part I was focusing on the work and so forth until I got out of law school.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:36.000
If you were, can you just sketch the early career path that you bring into the law?

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:45.000
I went from law school to being a law clerk for Judge Paul Hayes on the United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit,

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:55.000
which was a one-year position, and then I came to Washington, and for a few months I worked for a commissioner as a special assistant to a commissioner on the Federal Trade Commission,

00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:01.000
and in the spring of 1963 I went to work for, was then a autofotus importer as an associate.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:06.000
What was then a very small, comparatively small law firm in Washington?

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:12.000
And anticipating at the time that that would be a position to stay with for some time I would imagine.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:14.000
What were perhaps on it?

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:21.000
Yes, I guess that's true. I had certain illusions about what that firm was all about.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:33.000
Abe Fortis had just handled a very famous case in the Supreme Court involving the right to counsel in state court criminal proceedings,

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:40.000
and I kind of got the mistake in naive idea that was going to be a lot of that kind of thing at the law firm.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:52.000
The thermonautiled had been a prominent and representing individuals who have been called before the Macauliffe Committee and other committees along the lines of the Macauliffe Committee,

00:03:52.000 --> 00:04:00.000
so I had stars in my eyes about what it was and turned out to be quite different.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:09.000
Tell me how you first got connected to the Lawyers Constitutional Defense Committee?

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:19.000
In 1964, the spring of 1964, two friends of mine colleagues at Autofotus import a young man like myself,

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:35.000
they came aware and told me about the Lawyers Constitutional Defense Committee, which was sending lawyers in the summer to the South to help with the arrests that is essentially were resulting from all the civil rights activity that was taking place.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:47.000
I volunteered to go in 1964, but a lot of other people did as well, and I wasn't accepted for the reason that they were looking for lawyers who were admitted in the states,

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:58.000
which these problems were most manifest, and I wasn't my two friends who were admitted in Florida, and they were sent down there.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:13.000
I was kind of unhappy that I wasn't allowed to do this, and during the course of the following winter, I met the director of the program, Henry Schwartz Child, at the home of one of these two men, and I complained to him about this,

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:27.000
and he promised me that I'd be selected next summer, and I was, and in the summer of 1965, I was, they would send lawyers for three weeks on the lawyers' vacations.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:44.000
I was told I was going to be included, but I didn't know where, and a letter came that said you assigned a new Orleans Louisiana, which was a big disappointment to me, because I wanted to go to Selma, Alabama, or Jackson, Mississippi, or someplace that I had heard of, where things were happening.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:47.000
Of course, things were happening here, I just didn't know it.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:06:11.000
But that letter changed my life, because I got here the first of August 1965, and I spent my three weeks outlined a little bit in those documents I gave you what I did during those times, but it was very enlightening or weakening for me, because a couple of factors.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:26.000
One is where I was working in Washington, when there was a case, they'd put four lawyers on it, and sometimes lawyers full-time would work on one case, and the case would take years, and that was kind of the way of life.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:35.000
Here, things were happening with breakneck speed. When I showed up for work the first day, I asked them what I could do.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:58.000
They said, drive up to Baton Rouge and meet Murphy Bell. He has a school case he wants to bring, and I did, and I went to Baton Rouge and met this gentleman, who was the key black lawyer in that area for civil rights things, and he said that the people in St. Francisville, Westphalishian of Parish, want to bring a school desigregation case.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:12.000
I said, fine, and I went up there, and I met them, and I got their names and addresses and consents, and so forth, and went back to New Orleans, and a desigregation case by that school desigregation case by that time was a pretty stock thing.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:22.000
You get someone else's complaint, and you put the new names in, and I did, and I filed it in Baton Rouge, which is the district for that location.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:35.000
The judge there was a well-known racist judge named Igor and West, and he would just throw all these cases out in a minute they got there, even though it was established law of the land that these cases were proper cases.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:47.000
And the day after I filed it, the case was dismissed, and I filed a motion in the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals for a summary reversal of Judge West's decision.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:57.000
And a week later, the Fifth Circuit reversed the decision and sent it back for the entry of an order. In fact, they told them exactly what order to enter.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:08.000
So I'd been there for eight days, and I had gotten relief in a school desigregation case in the face, or the worst judge in the South, or practically one of them anyway.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:19.000
And that was just one of several things I did during three weeks, and I could just see the impact I could have in this situation.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:33.000
A lot of the lawyers who were being sent down by LCDC were also enjoying the life in New Orleans and bringing their wives and different things that seemed to me a little bit of a messy situation.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:41.000
And that I came away with the firm idea that what they need is permanent lawyers down there, and not people passing through.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:09:02.000
And I was working with the law firm, Collins Douglas and Eli, which is a very important, the most important firm in civil rights law in Louisiana, three young black lawyers who became the attorneys for the Congress of Racial Equality, which was the dominant civil rights organization in Louisiana.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:12.000
And I became friends with them, we liked each other, and we began to talk about my coming down on a more permanent basis, and one thing led to another at the time.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:24.000
There was a permanent staff member in Jackson, Mississippi, which was the main office. And over that winter, Mr. Schwartz, child raised the money to have a permanent lawyer in New Orleans.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:32.000
And I was going to be it, and following summer, I came down as an employee in today.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:35.000
So that's the summer of 60.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:37.000
Six.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:45.000
Let me take you back. It's so interesting to hear you talk about your arrival down here at S first three weeks.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:48.000
Can you say a little bit about, had you traveled in the South previously?

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:56.000
No. I've gotten as far as Charleston, South Carolina. I know, sightseeing.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:01.000
You mentioned this impression that's made upon a young lawyer by the experience you just just did.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:03.000
Getting this bit perversal.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:15.000
I'm interested also to hear about, as you might recall, the other impressions that you formed earlier, the civil rights context in the South as you saw it when you came in hints in that someone in 65.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:29.000
Well, the office of Collins, Douglas, and Eli was on the second floor in the 2200 block of Dryad Street.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:34.000
And then the ground floor in the storefront was the Congress or racial equality office.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:41.000
So I was meeting all these civil rights workers. So I wouldn't consider myself a civil rights worker.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:46.000
I was a lawyer doing his law work, but they were all coming through.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:52.000
People I had heard of and read about and action was taking place everywhere.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:59.000
Not including Bougalooza. Bougalooza was always the most active place, partly because it's so close.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:05.000
And it was easy to get in and out. It didn't take two days around trip to do something.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:14.000
But I met the people, all the people in Bougalooza and Bob Hicks, Gail Jenkins, A.C. Young, or T. Young, many people.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:17.000
There was an affinity growing up in me.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:28.000
And I just wanted to be part of it on a more permanent basis than this little snapshot that I got.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:35.000
And any impression I had that it wasn't civil rights activity in Southern Louisiana was completely dispelled.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:39.000
I was mentioning in terms of my letter that I got.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:44.000
And that's where I was my impression.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:48.000
Tell me a little more about the street black lawyers you met.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:56.000
There among the first African American lawyers in Louisiana, but not the first.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:04.000
They're older men who have streets named after them in New Orleans, AP Turo, and the best example.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:07.000
They were about ten years younger than he was.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:16.000
Robert Collins, who later became a federal judge, the first black federal judge in the South.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:28.000
Nils Douglas, who died just a few years ago, and who was probably the most active of the three in terms of the representation to core.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:37.000
And Lollice Eli, who was still my dear friend, and lives right down the block from here.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:43.000
They were completely different seeing an Arnold Fordous importer.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:47.000
They were scraping and making a living. They weren't getting paid much by core.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:54.000
They were very glad to have the help with the civil rights work, which freed them to do something that made a little money.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:13:06.000
They would do the kind of work you do in a poor black neighborhood, automobile accidents, bankruptcies, land law-attentant issues.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:11.000
But they were having a good time about it.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:18.000
Every day at the end of the three, the one who had the largest office room was Bob Collins.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:22.000
Everybody would gather in there. He had a bottle of scotch in his bottom drawer.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:25.000
People would have a drink and talk about what they did.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:30.000
It was a very attractive, friendly situation.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:35.000
Things were very stirring up at Arnold importer.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:40.000
This was a nice contrast.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:51.000
Were you a little bit about if you would, some of your first impressions of Bob Collins?

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:57.000
My first word comes to mind as hot.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:02.000
It was hot and smelly because of the paper mill.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:08.000
At that time, they were having a meeting every single night.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:16.000
There was the Bougalus of Otisley and the people who were the forefront with the people I mentioned.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:19.000
Robert Hicks, Gail Jenkins.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:24.000
There was a union hall right near Robert Hicks's house.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:28.000
There was a meeting in a rally every single night.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.000
Activities were planned.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:33.000
There was a long period of time in Bougalusa.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:37.000
There was a protest march on Main Street.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:43.000
The main street, in protested discrimination by the store owners.

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:48.000
I would go on every day after school.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:52.000
The Civil Rights Act had just passed.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:54.000
I'll put it this way.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:15:00.000
The Title VII of the Civil Rights Act had just come into effect four weeks earlier.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:04.000
There was a lot of focus on conditions at Crown Zellaback,

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:09.000
which was the major employer in town had four plants

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:14.000
of paper products, boxes, wrapping paper, different things.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:20.000
One of the things I did during my three weeks that for a summer was to work on the EEOC charge

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:27.000
which was a prerequisite to filing a Title VII action in court.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:35.000
Meeting a lot of the employees at the plants and hearing what they were doing or what their problems were.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:41.000
There were things going on in the criminal court.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:47.000
There were arrests coming out of these marches and arrests for other reasons,

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:51.000
harassment arrests, and there was a city court.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:58.000
I appeared at least twice in a city court of Bougalusa,

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:04.000
which was completely segregated, and had this very angry judge sitting on the bench.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:10.000
The first time I appeared, I mean, different to say,

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:15.000
Abe Fortis had just been appointed to the Supreme Court like the week I left.

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:18.000
And Nils Douglas was with me and he stood up and said,

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:21.000
please, the court, I want to introduce to the court Richard Sobel,

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:25.000
who comes from the law firm in Washington, D.C.,

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:29.000
from which the most recent Supreme Court nominee has come.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:34.000
And this judge used a crutch, one crutch to walk, he took his crutch,

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:37.000
and he slammed it on the table and he said,

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:42.000
don't talk to me about the Supreme Court of the United States.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:46.000
And that was my introduction to the city court,

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:49.000
but he let me say what I wanted,

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:57.000
and I was before him at least two or three times in those three weeks.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:04.000
I'm interested to hear a little bit too about some of your first impressions about

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:15.000
some of your first impressions about how it felt for you to be stepping into this landscape personally.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:17.000
I mean, you mentioned that, aside from the legal side,

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:25.000
did you, was there more complex set of concerns for you to have your safety about?

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:27.000
Well, nothing that happened just before I got here,

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:32.080
was that a bomb had been set off, had been tossed in the hallway to the Collins-Dufflesin

00:17:32.080 --> 00:17:36.000
or Eli office, so that was a conversation piece.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:39.000
Somehow that, I don't recall that bothering me.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:46.000
I came down here with my wife, my then wife, and two children.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:50.000
We found a nice apartment uptown that we could rent,

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:54.000
and just a block away from where little is Eli lived at the time.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:18:01.000
And it all seemed fine to me.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:07.000
I didn't have any, I was so excited to be involved in it,

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:10.000
and grateful in a way to be involved in it,

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:12.000
and everybody was approving of what I was doing,

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:14.000
you know, my wife then was, and everybody.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:16.000
So I didn't have concerns.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:20.000
I just got right into it, and when I arrived,

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:24.000
there was a volunteer, a regular volunteer,

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:27.000
had been down several times, named Jerry Gutman,

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:30.000
and Jerry at my gutman from New York City,

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:36.000
who filled out a file card for each pending case in the office.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:39.000
And when I got there, he wanted me to,

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:42.000
I sat down with him and he wanted to go over each file card,

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:47.000
well, the file cards were about four inches thick,

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:50.000
and everyone had a case, and I was the lawyer,

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:54.000
and every single one of those cases has of that day.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:58.000
So it was, there wasn't a lot of time to be, you know,

00:18:58.000 --> 00:18:59.000
be worried about it.

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:01.000
I just got got into it, and it was doing it,

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:05.000
trying to organize it, and some, and I worked alone,

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:10.000
but I honestly did basically the civil rights work

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:14.000
with, I was in association with the lawyers upstairs,

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:19.000
but basically I was supposed to take the lead

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:21.000
and make sure these things happened,

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:27.000
and I did that alone for about four or five months.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:32.000
You see, I was so much, I felt they shouldn't have this volunteer

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:36.000
lawyer program, and I convinced Henry Schwartz's child

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:40.000
that, see, what they did is they flew the lawyers in,

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:42.000
they paid the airfare, and they paid the hotel bills.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:46.000
Well, you could hire a lawyer if it was less than that,

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:49.000
and, but the problem was there weren't many lawyers

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:51.000
in Louisiana who wanted to do that,

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:54.000
and, but I found one, a fellow named Don Juno,

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:58.000
who had recently graduated from Tulane,

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:00.000
and he was, he's a very unusual person,

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:03.000
and he's white, he's very unusual person,

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:05.000
and he wanted to do this, so by December,

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:09.000
I came down, full time, late July, by December,

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:12.000
he had joined the office, and so we had two lawyers,

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:15.000
which was great, and I stopped having,

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:17.000
pretty much stopped having the volunteers,

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:19.000
which was kind of a distraction,

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:22.000
and I think by the following summer,

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:25.000
I had three, I had two lawyers with addition to myself,

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:27.000
it got to be three, one point I reached four,

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:29.000
so we really had a law of this going,

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:32.000
and a lot of help and so on.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:34.000
Let me ask you about the, the complaint filed in 65,

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:36.000
some of the before from there,

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:40.000
did, did, one of the reasons that you like

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:42.000
have an active LDF connection?

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:44.000
You go to the next one, go to the next one.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:48.000
No, they didn't, they knew all the people and all,

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:52.000
but they were core lawyers,

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:56.000
and there was, there was a core organization,

00:20:56.000 --> 00:21:00.000
you know, LDF started as the nonprofit part of the NAACP,

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:02.000
now of course, it's completely different,

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:04.000
but there was a core thing that was called

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:08.000
the scholarship education, defense fund for racial equality.

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:11.000
The call was the Congress of racial equality,

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:14.000
and that was their client,

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:18.000
and that was where the input from New York City

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:20.000
would come in.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:22.000
There was a man named Carl Racklin,

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:24.000
who was the head of it,

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:26.000
and he would come in and out of town.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:30.000
You mentioned filing a complaint that day was July 15,

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:32.000
65, just after,

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:34.000
not two weeks after the act is taken.

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:36.000
Tell the seventh's taken effect.

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:41.000
Actually, in those early days,

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:44.000
you mentioned that you could borrow a boilerplate

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:46.000
filing on the school side,

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:48.000
but you know that the problem.

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:51.000
Well, that complaint, you say July 15, 1965,

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:53.000
I was not here yet,

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:55.000
but I thought the complaint,

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:57.000
the charge wasn't complete enough,

00:21:57.000 --> 00:21:59.000
and I redid it,

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:04.000
to list the practices more specifically,

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:06.000
that I thought were a problem.

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:09.000
How they did the one in July,

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:11.000
I don't know, I would guess it was a rushed job,

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:13.000
just from the circumstances.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:15.000
The one I filed,

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:17.000
I had listed a lot of issues

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:19.000
that later became prominent issues,

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:21.000
testing and seniority,

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:25.000
and segregated local unions

00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:27.000
and different things that were,

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:29.000
I don't think mentioned in the first charge,

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:31.000
but it was, that,

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:33.000
you had to start over on a blank sheet of paper

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:34.000
for that one,

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:36.000
and unlike the school's segregation with a gation,

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:38.000
which was going on, you know,

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:39.000
for quite some time,

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:41.000
there was this famous new all-in-school desegregation case

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:43.000
many years before,

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:45.000
much more established.

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:48.000
Did you have to rival in early summer 2006?

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:51.000
Did you have an active pattern of communication

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:56.000
with the part of L.D.F that was engaged in early title seven work?

00:22:56.000 --> 00:22:58.000
No, I didn't.

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:00.000
I don't think L.D.F,

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:03.000
if they had a title seven case in Louisiana,

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:05.000
I don't know what it was.

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:07.000
I don't think they did.

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:10.000
Did you wouldn't have called up to folks working on these issues

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:11.000
in New York City to say,

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:13.000
hey, what are you guys doing on these L.D.F?

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:14.000
On the title seven front?

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:15.000
No.

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:17.000
I'd love to know some of you to dry out

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:19.000
the part about the loose stuff,

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:21.000
but I don't think they did.

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:24.000
Did you wouldn't have called up to folks working on these issues

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:25.000
in New York City to say,

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:27.000
well, the part about the loose stuff,

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:31.000
some of your impressions about these key three individuals

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:34.000
you mentioned and how and why it was that

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:39.000
for the loose stuff had become such an active place for struggle?

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:44.000
It's the last question first.

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:47.000
It became active because of the three individuals,

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:49.000
and I think if they had been somewhere else,

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:51.000
it would have been active somewhere else.

00:23:52.000 --> 00:23:56.000
They had an unbelievable commitment and drive

00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:00.000
and perseverance to what they were trying to achieve.

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:04.000
And there were two other factors.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:07.000
There was the Crown Zellabak Mill,

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:10.000
which employed thousands of, I don't know,

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:12.000
maybe a thousand people.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:15.000
And it wasn't one of these southern towns.

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:17.000
There were nobody really has a job.

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:20.000
You know, they're making out in various ways,

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:23.000
these are union workers and an union contract,

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:25.000
and they were used to organization.

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:29.000
And the Far as Employment was concerned,

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:32.000
the complaints were quite clear.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:40.000
And because Crown Zellabak was from San Francisco,

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:44.000
a group in San Francisco took a very active interest

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:47.000
in supporting what they were doing,

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:49.000
including sending money.

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:53.000
Primarily sending money.

00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:55.000
What did black workers were attempting to do?

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:58.000
What the Buggalus of Wooders League was trying to do.

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:02.000
And they were pressuring Crown through the San Francisco community

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:03.000
to make changes.

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:06.000
Crown never would make changes until they were forced to,

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:08.000
but they were getting that pressure.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:12.000
So the fact that there was that input from San Francisco

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:16.000
was important in terms of not that the movement was financed

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:17.000
in any significant way.

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:19.000
But if they wanted to buy placards for signs,

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:21.000
there was a little kitty to do that.

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:26.000
And each of these people got a trip to San Francisco,

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:28.000
which they had never been out of Louisiana.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:31.000
And it kind of gave them a broad scope about what was going on,

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:35.000
some recognition and a national location.

00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:38.000
So I think those things are unusual about Buggalusa.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:45.000
It's a, I can't really compare it to a lot of other towns.

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:50.000
As far as my observation was, it was kind of the hottest line,

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:52.000
segregationist mall city.

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:54.000
There wasn't much leeway.

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:59.000
And that continues to today, as far as I'm concerned, up there.

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:05.000
Many, many years later in the 1990s, 1990s,

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:08.000
after I was living in Washington, lost touch,

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:12.000
sort of, came back, moved back, reconnected with my friends in Buggalusa.

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:18.000
Gail Jenkins encouraged me to represent some police officers,

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:22.000
black police officers, with their complaints about lesser treatment,

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:24.000
discriminatory treatment they were getting.

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:27.000
And they would have been easy things to correct.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:31.000
But the mayor would not give one inch on it.

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:35.000
It was just remarkable that 45 years had gone by

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:39.000
and asking for things like posting the opportunities for training.

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:43.000
So it's not just bored of mouth among the white officers.

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:45.000
Didn't want to do that.

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:48.000
Things like that, there were bigger things too,

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:50.000
but they wouldn't do anything.

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:54.000
So Buggalusa has kind of a particular hard line about everything

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:57.000
that I think kind of provoked more activity.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:02.000
I assume in some other places in Louisiana when the storekeepers

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:05.000
got the kind of pressure they were getting in Buggalusa,

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:09.000
you know, there were things like being able to try on clothes

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:11.000
or not.

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:14.000
Middle things, it seems like little things,

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:16.000
but there was never any give up there.

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:18.000
So I think that had to do it.

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:21.000
All right, now about the people.

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:24.000
When I came back to Louisiana in the 90s,

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:27.000
I spent a lot of time talking with Gail Jenkins.

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:30.000
In fact, I recorded conversations with her.

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:35.000
And not that she was bragging at anything,

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:39.000
but I got the firm impression that she was the spark

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:47.000
that created an organization that could take on the role

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:49.000
of Buggalusa, vote as Lee took on.

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:51.000
The only thing I particularly mentioned

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:54.000
is that she wanted a man to lead it.

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:58.000
And she didn't feel, she felt it would be more effective

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:01.000
if a man led it.

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:05.000
And I think she even mentioned a large man.

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:07.000
I'm not sure of that.

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:10.000
I may be adding that pop, but I know they're the plots, too.

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:13.000
And there was this man, A.C. Young,

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:17.000
who was an outspoken kind of well-known guy in the community.

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:22.000
And she approached him and asked him to do this according to her.

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:24.000
I never discussed this with A.C.

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:26.000
And she wanted to think about it.

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:28.000
And ultimately, he said he would do it.

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:30.000
And when he did it, he jumped in with both feet,

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:33.000
and he did everything he read her.

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:36.000
And her cousin was Bob Hicks.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:43.000
And she encouraged him to get in, and he did.

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:50.000
He and his wife both, and they all played tremendously significant roles.

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:53.000
Hicks was a more...

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:00.000
Not so flamboyant as A.C. Young,

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:03.000
and could get more into the details of lawsuits.

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:08.000
And he became the plaintiff in a lot of the things we did.

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:13.000
He could testify very well, and not...

00:29:15.000 --> 00:29:17.000
And many other attributes.

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:19.000
And their home on Ninth Street,

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:23.000
which they've since named Robert Hicks Avenue, I think,

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:27.000
was the center place for anyone coming to Bogolusa

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:30.000
in connection with Civil Rights.

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:32.000
And it wasn't just lawyers.

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:34.000
It was Civil Rights workers.

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:38.000
There was a call worker in town.

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:42.000
James Farmer came to Bogolusa.

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:45.000
Other men named Lincoln Lynch,

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:47.000
I don't know what that name means any new,

00:29:47.000 --> 00:29:51.000
but he was the second in command in Kour.

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:53.000
He came to Bogolusa,

00:29:53.000 --> 00:29:56.000
and everything would always happen at the Hicks House,

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:59.000
with food.

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:05.000
And there were these stories that I little bit precede my time,

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:08.000
but about the men on the roof on the Hicks House,

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:12.000
in response to threats that he had received,

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:14.000
because of what he was doing.

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:18.000
And so there was a show of readiness to fight back there.

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:20.000
I'm in on the roof with rifles,

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:22.000
and nobody came.

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:24.000
It's that kind of thing.

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:27.000
And Hicks was up for that,

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:32.000
and he certainly never backed down for a second.

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:35.000
So they all played somewhat different roles.

00:30:35.000 --> 00:30:37.000
When there was time to give a speech,

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:38.000
or to Big Rally,

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:40.000
he easy young would give it.

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:44.000
He was a frontman in the marching line,

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:48.000
and a lot of people had tremendous amount of respect

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:50.000
in the community.

00:30:50.000 --> 00:30:54.000
And Hicks was right next to him,

00:30:54.000 --> 00:30:58.000
but a little bit more subdued about things,

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:01.000
a little bit more into the schedule,

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:03.000
into what date something's going to happen,

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:04.000
that kind of thing.

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:05.000
So I'm making myself clear.

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:07.000
And you couldn't have one without the other,

00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:09.000
and it was a wonderful combination.

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:10.000
They didn't fight.

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:11.000
No competition.

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:13.000
AZ was the president.

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:15.000
And Bob was the vice president,

00:31:15.000 --> 00:31:17.000
and Gail was the secretary,

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:19.000
and never changed.

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:22.000
And I was very nice.

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:25.000
Someone else who came to Bogolusa

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:27.000
were the Freedom Singers,

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:29.000
and the Freedom Theater.

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:30.000
Was that what it was called?

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:33.000
The Free Southern Theater came to Bogolusa.

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:34.000
It took the Union Hall,

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:35.000
where they had their meetings.

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:36.000
They had a performance.

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:37.000
The Freedom Singers came.

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:38.000
They had a performance.

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:42.000
So it was attracting that kind of potential.

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:44.000
So I was a little bit more worried about it.

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:47.000
I was a little worried about it.

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:49.000
We're back.

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:52.000
So I want to ask about,

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:55.000
after round 166,

00:31:55.000 --> 00:31:58.000
you pursued the Crown Zellbot case, obviously,

00:31:58.000 --> 00:31:59.000
and pushed forward,

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:01.000
and would come trial in the summer 67, I think.

00:32:01.000 --> 00:32:02.000
Correct.

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:03.000
Which could grow in Canada.

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:04.000
Right.

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:07.000
Would that try to work in some sense?

00:32:07.000 --> 00:32:13.000
Can you talk about that process of pushing a Title VII case forward,

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:16.000
moving it towards trial in that moment?

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:20.000
There's not a lot of...

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:23.000
There aren't cases that the field was selling you to the law.

00:32:23.000 --> 00:32:25.000
Yeah.

00:32:28.000 --> 00:32:30.000
By that summer 67,

00:32:30.000 --> 00:32:34.000
we had filed additional cases involving other plants in Bogolusa,

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:37.000
and they came to trial,

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:40.000
was consolidated with a government case,

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:43.000
United States versus local one.

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:47.000
Well, when I was practicing law in Washington,

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:51.000
I was doing a lot of antitrust cases.

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:54.000
And I became familiar,

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:58.000
very familiar with discovery, depositions,

00:32:58.000 --> 00:33:00.000
production of documents,

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:05.000
which the lawyers who hadn't had that experience

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:09.000
didn't really have any familiarity with and weren't doing.

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:14.000
And I got into a more methodical mode of filing the interrogatories,

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:17.000
filing the request for production of documents,

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:23.000
filing motions to compel the scarry when the responses were not forthcoming,

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:28.000
scheduling depositions before the hearing and taking them.

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:31.000
And it would be more of a...

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:34.000
One reason is I had the money to do that

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:37.000
because LCDC was paying for deposition transcripts

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:40.000
and all that kind of thing.

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:44.000
But I had the distinct impression that

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:48.000
earlier they'd be more of a Russian to try to get into court a week afterwards

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:54.000
and not have all the homework done.

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:58.000
That was one thing that I organized, the material,

00:33:58.000 --> 00:34:00.000
and of course George was a tremendous help.

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:02.000
We kind of split the issues.

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:06.000
And he did a tremendous amount of research about testing

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:09.000
and the impact of testing on fair employment.

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:11.000
And that was a new issue at that time.

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:15.000
People really hadn't been talking about that.

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:18.000
And he got a lot of experts to help him,

00:34:18.000 --> 00:34:21.000
people and not lawyers, but people in the testing field.

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:23.000
So that was one major advantage.

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:28.000
Another was there was a new judge just appointed named Frederick Hebey,

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:32.000
who had nothing in his background would suggest he'd be sympathetic

00:34:32.000 --> 00:34:37.000
to these kind of cases, but he was sympathetic to these kind of cases.

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:45.000
And I, a lot of the cases, a lot of the litigation in Bogolusa,

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:48.000
went before Judge Hebey.

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:52.000
Not because of any special tricks, it just fell that way.

00:34:52.000 --> 00:34:54.000
He had the school case.

00:34:54.000 --> 00:35:02.000
He had both, he had all three employment discrimination cases.

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:04.000
Other cases.

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:07.000
The school cases in Bogolusa, see,

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:11.000
they went further than any other school cases because they wanted to litigate

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:16.000
about who would be the prom queen and how the football players

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:17.000
are being treated.

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:21.000
And every last thing, the people in Bogolusa would not accept

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:25.000
what they call the law, one vestige of discrimination.

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:28.000
I mean, they wanted to get everything out on the table.

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:30.000
And Judge Hebey would call a hearing.

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:34.000
I remember we had a two-day hearing on a Friday and Saturday

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:37.000
about the selection of the prom queen.

00:35:37.000 --> 00:35:41.000
And he treated as as serious as any other case he could have had.

00:35:41.000 --> 00:35:43.000
And it was very wonderful, really.

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:46.000
Because another judge could just throw you out, or not schedule it.

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:49.000
I mean, you don't get to trial because you want to get to trial.

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:52.000
You get to trial because the judge says, okay, here's the trial date.

00:35:52.000 --> 00:35:57.000
And so we've got a lot of cooperation from this man.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:36:00.000
See, the courts were so different that not only from Hebey

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:03.000
and he's not the only district judge that helped us out a lot.

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:10.000
But the Court of Appeals was just perfect in terms of what we wanted to do there.

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:13.000
These men who really cared about these things

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:15.000
and would give you, like I mentioned before,

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:17.000
about the school case in St. Francisville,

00:36:17.000 --> 00:36:21.000
they'd give you what you were entitled to overnight.

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:25.000
And so all those things coalesced, I didn't have to do that

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:30.000
when it's in the Hebey cases, but in other cases, I certainly did.

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:37.000
So I attributed more to those factors than anything else.

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:46.000
Some of the issues in the Crown's Eliva case were perfectly obvious.

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:49.000
The seniority issues and the testing issues were not.

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:52.000
And I mentioned George developed one, and I worked on the other.

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:56.000
And I got help from, it was a case in Virginia,

00:36:56.000 --> 00:37:00.000
corals against Philip Morris, that was a precedent.

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:06.000
And I think the first case really, was that later?

00:37:06.000 --> 00:37:10.000
Well, then it wasn't a precedent.

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:12.000
I thought there was a precedent in that case.

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:15.000
Maybe it came later as a precedent in some of our...

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:16.000
Okay, so...

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:17.000
Judge Fosson.

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:24.000
And yeah, and a woman in Gabrielle McDonald later became a federal judge in Texas

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:27.000
was a lawyer for the plaintiffs.

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:34.000
In addition, I began, you mentioned whether I was consulting with the lawyer's defense,

00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:42.000
legal defense fund, which I wasn't, but I did become in contact with the lawyers

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:44.000
from the Civil Rights Division of the Palm Nurgustus.

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:48.000
And they were doing a lot of thinking about these seniority issues.

00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:52.000
And really showed me some things I hadn't realized myself about them.

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:57.000
One guy particularly, Robert Moore and David Rose.

00:37:57.000 --> 00:38:01.000
And we tried the look 29 case together.

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:05.000
But even before that, the case case was tried first,

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:12.000
I was getting kind of different vantage points on how this seniority system

00:38:12.000 --> 00:38:17.000
can adversely affect black employees who had never been allowed into white jobs.

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:22.000
Need I say, before the Civil Rights Act will pass, there were black jobs and white jobs.

00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:26.000
There was no two ways of better, no fooling, no...

00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:29.000
And two unions, and each union had its own jobs in their contract.

00:38:29.000 --> 00:38:33.000
And a question is how you put that together, and it's complicated.

00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:40.000
And anyway, by the time we went to trial, I had it straight, and Judge Hebey boarded

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:42.000
an issued a preliminary judgment.

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:44.000
He did his issue as a written opinion until three years later,

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:47.000
but he issued an injunction at the end of the trial.

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:52.000
And so I guess that's the answer to your question.

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:55.000
Let me take you back at the bubble list and talk with me.

00:38:56.000 --> 00:38:58.000
You're grappling up there with...

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:04.000
And the mostly is grappling with the most basic things, education, jobs.

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:09.000
Can you talk a bit more about the...

00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:12.000
Some illustrious tale about the nature of the...

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:17.000
Kind of for our record here, what she saw in the schools, what she saw at Crown Zellerbach.

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:22.000
A little bit more of the fabric of that experience for those folks at the time.

00:39:22.000 --> 00:39:36.000
When we used to say a desegregation of what had been issued in the Southern School desegregation cases,

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:38.000
it was the most token.

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:41.000
The result was as token as it could possibly be.

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:44.000
It was what we've called then freedom of choice.

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:47.000
And every white student chose a white school,

00:39:47.000 --> 00:39:52.000
and two or three or four black kids pushed by their parents,

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:57.000
basically would go to the white school, and all the other black children

00:39:57.000 --> 00:39:59.000
would go to the same school they were going to.

00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:06.000
So I had occasion to visit even after there was a desegregation order in Bogolusa, the schools.

00:40:06.000 --> 00:40:09.000
And they were blatantly run down.

00:40:09.000 --> 00:40:13.000
I mean, they didn't look anything like the white schools looked.

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:18.000
And I interviewed teachers, and I heard about how they would pay less,

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:24.000
and didn't get the supplies they needed.

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:28.000
And you could just walk by the school and see what the building looked like,

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:32.000
and what they were dilapidated.

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:38.000
And that motivated our office to really press that particular issue,

00:40:38.000 --> 00:40:41.000
which is one of the things I spent a lot of time working on,

00:40:41.000 --> 00:40:46.000
which was eliminating freedom of choice and reestablishing the school districts

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:50.000
in some kind of non-racial way that everybody goes to the school in the other house.

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:59.000
And the first place that was ordered, I think, in the south, was in Washington Parish by Judge Hebe.

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:03.000
I got the citation of the case and that material I gave you.

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:08.000
And then later on, we achieved similar relief in the Supreme Court of the United States

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:13.000
on a south wall, on a whole regional basis that had to happen right away.

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:15.000
It couldn't be, there was no more deliberate speed.

00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:19.000
Those were very important issues, because the status of school desegregation,

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:24.000
as I found it when I got to the south, I'm not saying about the big cities that I never was in,

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:31.000
a big city case like New Orleans, but in these small towns, it amounted just little next to nothing.

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:39.000
And of course, the children who had to do this, I'm just reading Shullian Hunter's book

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:42.000
about her going to the University of Georgia.

00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:46.000
And the children that had to do this had to put up with quite a bit.

00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:52.000
It wasn't just going to school anymore, these eight and nine-year-olds being these heroes,

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:58.000
and that's not fair. And anyway, so that was a school situation.

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:08.000
By the time I left my job at LCDC, there still was no significant integration of the school.

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:13.000
Some bogeyless happened to fall in here.

00:42:13.000 --> 00:42:21.000
With respect to the paper mill, of course, I got familiar with the man I became the lawyer for the black union.

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:26.000
I was able to tour the plant and see the jobs.

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:34.000
And of course, a lot of the defenses about these seniority issues was that the black employees were incompetent to do,

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:40.000
hadn't been trained. They wanted everybody to go up step by step and get at the back of the line, essentially,

00:42:40.000 --> 00:42:43.000
and learn, but some of these men were 50 and 55 years old.

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:46.000
They didn't have any time to get at the back of the line.

00:42:46.000 --> 00:42:53.000
And I began to observe the jobs, and they were with very few exceptions, quite simple jobs.

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:57.000
And I could see by just watching them what the men were doing.

00:42:57.000 --> 00:43:05.000
I was in there by court order to view the plants that anything complicated, like fixing a broken machine,

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:08.000
they'd call it a craftsman who was specializing in that machine.

00:43:08.000 --> 00:43:14.000
But in terms of a working machine, the production of corrugated board is a very simple process.

00:43:14.000 --> 00:43:24.000
It's a repetitive process. And it might take, and I've always been cynical about the amount of training you need for things.

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:31.000
I would say in two or three days maximum, any reasonably intelligent person could have done any of those jobs.

00:43:31.000 --> 00:43:34.000
They wanted them to wait 25 years.

00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:43.000
So I saw what it was on the ground, and that, of course, encouraged me, because I didn't know anything about making paper.

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:53.000
I hadn't gotten encouraged me to, in my legal pursuits, by seeing what was actually involved in these jobs.

00:43:53.000 --> 00:43:57.000
And, of course, the pay scales were dramatically different.

00:43:57.000 --> 00:44:09.000
The highest paying black job under the pre-Title 7 Union contract was picking the final product off the assembly line and putting it on pallets.

00:44:09.000 --> 00:44:14.000
And that was the highest paying job. They were sweeping the floor job. They were lesser jobs.

00:44:14.000 --> 00:44:24.000
And the white job started a notch above that job, and would go up six or seven steps to what was really good blue collar pay at that time.

00:44:24.000 --> 00:44:35.000
So, and that got into, it kind of slid into a sex discrimination issue, because they wouldn't, they had two bags.

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:46.000
There was a box plant, two bag plants, making two different types of paper bags, and a paper mill, which takes wood, and turns it into paper.

00:44:46.000 --> 00:45:00.000
The bag plants were all white, and no, I'm trying to get, there were no women in the box planted.

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:09.000
It was an aspect of sex discrimination about the bag plants. It slips my mind right now, but they had us, I know what it was.

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:17.000
They didn't employ women at all, regardless of race, in the box plant and the paper mill, but they employed them in the bag plant.

00:45:17.000 --> 00:45:23.000
And the bag plant, they were no black employees at all. The bag plants, plural.

00:45:23.000 --> 00:45:33.000
And so it kind of became a combination of sex and race. And I noticed that touring the plant, that there were no black employees.

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:44.000
And they had a separate black union for the box plant and a separate one for the paper mill, but no black union, of course, for the other ones, because there were no black employees.

00:45:44.000 --> 00:45:57.000
So a lot of being able to get in there and be on the scene. And as I said before about Bougalus, I had clients in upstate New York and into Lula, Louisiana, which is as high as you can go, and still be in Louisiana.

00:45:57.000 --> 00:46:11.000
I had clients in Monroe, and what's that pretty town where Stanley lives to the west of here?

00:46:11.000 --> 00:46:21.000
But I didn't get over there. There had to be an event for me to go that far. But Bougalus, I was there all the time.

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:26.000
So it was very, you get a deeper understanding of what's going on.

00:46:26.000 --> 00:46:28.000
Did you pick a golden back in the day or kind of know what you had?

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:35.000
Oh, sure. I would, I never slept in Bougalus. I made a rule of thumb not to sleep in those places.

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:42.000
Because I guess that was my fear of violence. That I just didn't want to be asleep in one of the motels in these towns.

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:50.000
I would go to Faraday, Louisiana, which was another civil rights hotspot, and I'd cross the bridge in the Mississippi and stay in matches.

00:46:50.000 --> 00:47:02.000
And when I went to Toulula, I would cross the bridge and stay in Vicksburg, because I just always had a feeling it wouldn't be a good idea to be sleeping alone in one of these motels.

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:09.000
So I never stayed in Bougalus. There was no reason to actually. It was, it was about 90 minutes.

00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:19.000
But they would, at least in the early stages, they would drive me to the border of Washington, Parish, to see me out.

00:47:19.000 --> 00:47:26.000
And I never knew whether that was, I never really, I don't know what that was necessary, not necessary.

00:47:26.000 --> 00:47:33.000
In fact, there's never any problem. And it may be because they were driving me. But I always came home.

00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:37.000
I'm a theme of risk of violence and all of that.

00:47:37.000 --> 00:47:42.000
Bougalus, obviously, has a pretty active chapter of the Deacon's for the fence.

00:47:42.000 --> 00:47:45.000
You're saying now they do? No, but I think they do.

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:59.000
And I'm wondering your perspective on the implications of the Deacons in the community and say in relation to the civil rights activities of the voters league.

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:07.000
Well, okay. I have a rather unorthodox view about the Deacons and the fence.

00:48:07.000 --> 00:48:18.000
In the time I was living here and working on problems in Bougalusa, I never heard about the Deacons and the fence.

00:48:18.000 --> 00:48:33.000
I never maybe overstates it. Maybe I heard about it. But there was certainly no members to meet the sort of guy from the Deacons and everything was under the Bougalusa voters league.

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:44.000
I did know about how when there was some threats of violence against the Hicks household, friends of theirs came and climbed on the roof and spent the night with rifles.

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:53.000
Now that gets to be a Deacons and defense story. At the time, I think it was friends of the Hicks coming over there with their rifles.

00:48:54.000 --> 00:49:00.000
So I just don't, I think there's something about the Deacons story is very attractive to historians.

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:07.000
I'm not saying that. Because I hear so much about it now and I heard nothing about it.

00:49:07.000 --> 00:49:14.000
And I've spoken with Louis Eli about this extensively and he agrees with me.

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:21.000
So I don't know. Not really what I have to say about it.

00:49:21.000 --> 00:49:32.000
I did, like I say, when I left town, not for long, but in the early days, 65 and maybe the first few must 65.

00:49:32.000 --> 00:49:37.000
Somebody would want to follow me down in a car down to the border.

00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:44.000
But the word Deacon was never mentioned and I didn't even think I saw any guns. I didn't see any guns.

00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:49.000
I never saw any guns actually. I get right down to it.

00:49:49.000 --> 00:49:56.000
So I read these stories about people had their trunk full of rifles. I just don't know what this is all about.

00:49:56.000 --> 00:50:03.000
Maybe I was just naive, but that's my honest thing I can tell you. That's my impression.

00:50:03.000 --> 00:50:08.000
Do you have any sense of the claim?

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:11.000
Yes.

00:50:11.000 --> 00:50:16.000
I think there was some clan violence against some of the mortgages.

00:50:16.000 --> 00:50:24.000
I'm a little indistinct about it in my mind, but I think there was.

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:32.000
And I don't know who could tell you now exactly who was there because the main people are in a round right now.

00:50:32.000 --> 00:50:45.000
But I don't think it was massive in any way. I mean, there was bad. I think there was one or two occasions where a shot was fired during a march and somebody was hurt.

00:50:45.000 --> 00:50:50.000
I'm just not that clear. It didn't happen when I was around.

00:50:50.000 --> 00:50:55.000
The Bougalus movement was way underway long before I got here.

00:50:55.000 --> 00:51:03.000
And some of the most important things that were going to happen had already happened. Hicks against night. You're familiar with that case.

00:51:03.000 --> 00:51:08.000
I had nothing to do with whatsoever. It was concluded the day before I arrived as a volunteer.

00:51:08.000 --> 00:51:24.000
But it had been Robert Hicks and several others taking on the chief of police because of lack of protection of marches, which certainly means to me there must have been some harassing of marches.

00:51:24.000 --> 00:51:36.000
So I'm not a good source for this because as I say, Judge Christian Berry, a very powerful man, put an injunction in against every police officer in town.

00:51:36.000 --> 00:51:46.000
I didn't see that kind of activity. I just didn't see it. So I don't really want to talk to them after about it because I don't know much about it really. But that's just my impression of it.

00:51:46.000 --> 00:51:58.000
But I do think there was violence. And when we marched to Baton Rouge, which was entering new territory, the word was out that the headquarters of the Cluj Cux clan is in Livingston Parish.

00:51:58.000 --> 00:52:09.000
And there was a lot of discussion and I was engaged in negotiations with state offices about where they're going to let them march through Livingston Parish. Although it's right on the way to Baton Rouge, but I suppose some other route could have been found.

00:52:09.000 --> 00:52:30.000
But because they felt there was going to be really violent, serious violence in Livingston Parish. And I don't know if you've ever seen the picture of the march going through Livingston Parish, but there were troopers lined up on each side of the marchers, which forming a barrier between the marches and the observers.

00:52:30.000 --> 00:52:53.000
And when it came, push came to shove with, and the godsmen who were there, I guess that's what they were, national godsmen, way outnumbered the marchers. So they were really being protected. And the only thing I actually saw was some soda bottles being, from glass soda bottles being thrown above the police to the land in the area where the marches were.

00:52:53.000 --> 00:53:06.000
But they had cleared the area of anybody that was going to had a gun or anything like that. So that was kind of a scary thing. But it didn't come to fruition in any serious way.

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:14.000
But we were thinking that the clan was in Livingston Parish. Although undoubtedly there were people.

00:53:14.000 --> 00:53:27.000
You know, organizations like the clan and the deacons that kind of murky, it's not like belonging to the ACLU. It's an attitude more than anything else. And it certainly had the attitude in Bogolusa, but I just didn't see much of it.

00:53:27.000 --> 00:53:31.000
I'm going to say that on the call.

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:33.000
I'm going to plug back in.

00:53:33.000 --> 00:53:34.000
You are.

00:53:34.000 --> 00:53:35.000
Okay.

00:53:35.000 --> 00:53:45.000
We're back after just a brief break. Some of that I'd like to take you back to turn again to the Picspecrancel about trial before Judge Hebe and summer 67.

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:50.000
Any sets and things about the judge, very interesting perspective.

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:54.000
He emerged in the end as someone who you were happy to be in front of.

00:53:54.000 --> 00:53:56.000
Yes, definitely.

00:53:56.000 --> 00:54:06.000
What's about the trial, special recollections or impressions, memories that persist?

00:54:06.000 --> 00:54:15.000
There were two issues that were really being litigated, the seniority issue and the testing issue.

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:19.000
And George showed, and they each side had witnesses.

00:54:19.000 --> 00:54:24.000
And George Cooper showed up at the trial with a trunk.

00:54:24.000 --> 00:54:27.000
I'm talking about the kind of trunk a kid would take to camp.

00:54:27.000 --> 00:54:35.000
A big trunk full of books that he had found that either the witnesses for the Fr. Trounds,

00:54:35.000 --> 00:54:43.000
Ella Beck had said the opposite things with what they were saying now or other experts demolishing what they were saying.

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:48.000
And he walked in the court, he opened the trunk, and he piled all these books on the council table.

00:54:48.000 --> 00:54:52.000
It was like a library. It was all all-road books.

00:54:52.000 --> 00:55:01.000
And each witness for crown, I'm telling you the highlights in my mind, George would start in with Fr. Trounds book.

00:55:01.000 --> 00:55:03.000
And he'd go through every book with them.

00:55:03.000 --> 00:55:07.000
And he just made them look like completed heets.

00:55:07.000 --> 00:55:16.000
And what seemed like a tough road to hoax is the test had nothing about race in it, you know how these tests are.

00:55:16.000 --> 00:55:33.000
By this process, he really made it clear to the judge who was open to having it made clear to him what the impact of these tests were and how useless they were for the purpose they were intended, which is to find good employees.

00:55:33.000 --> 00:55:41.000
We had our witnesses too on that issue which George had found and brought to New Orleans and testified and the crown had theirs.

00:55:41.000 --> 00:55:45.000
But it was the cross examination that sticks out in my mind.

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:59.000
And on the testing issue was on this seniority issue was a little less dramatic, but we did have charts and we had made charts to display in a way the judge could see it from the bench.

00:55:59.000 --> 00:56:12.000
What would be the impact of the existing seniority system versus one that did not incorporate the past and went on for quite a while.

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:16.000
The child did, I would guess it was something like eight days of trial.

00:56:16.000 --> 00:56:26.000
And with a lot of attendance from the people in Bogolusa, particularly of the crown's yellow back workers, Bob Hicks was sitting next to me the entire eight days.

00:56:27.000 --> 00:56:33.000
That's what I meant by. That's the kind of thing he could do. He'd keep the record straight. He'd help me with doing it.

00:56:33.000 --> 00:56:45.000
And the judge, I think, was impressed by that. I think he was, this man was changed. The judge was changed by his exposure to these civil rights cases.

00:56:46.000 --> 00:57:02.000
And I think one of them was the, there's a lot of feeling sometimes by a judge that the lawyers are ginning up the cases, are making up the theories and there really is no client. It's just a name.

00:57:02.000 --> 00:57:20.000
But by virtue of having 30 people from crown's yellow back in the courtroom completely, you know, got rid of any of that flavor and it really became what it was, which was a community that was committed to this.

00:57:20.000 --> 00:57:29.000
And that was not just in that case, but a lot of other cases before Judge Hebeal. I said he had the school case and a lot of kids came down to be there for it.

00:57:29.000 --> 00:57:40.000
That was another thing about the movement in Buggles. They responded to that kind of situation. They would do that. That's really what my thoughts are about the case.

00:57:40.000 --> 00:57:58.000
Honestly, I'm going to send you into the record that sometimes we pass right over for our purpose today. Could you just recap and brief terms the introduction of things like the Wonderlick test and how they were employed and why it became something that had to be fought against?

00:57:58.000 --> 00:58:27.000
The Wonderlick test is a short answer test, maybe 20 questions, 30 questions at most, which tested very simple forms of knowledge, including definitions of words, knowledge of geography,

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:53.000
and spatial relation things. And it had been used, it was a device that had been used for years around the country as some kind of minimal intelligence to get a job thing when there was no issues about race just involved.

00:58:53.000 --> 00:59:05.000
The Wonderlick test was done by the WIthesack test until the Civil Rights Act passed. So none of these white workers and these supposedly difficult jobs had ever passed the test.

00:59:05.000 --> 00:59:11.000
They made it a requirement for employment. White or black had passed the test.

00:59:11.000 --> 00:59:27.000
The statistics showed, well, I showed two things. One is that historically and in Bogolusa, the white pass rate was much higher than the black pass rate. Three things had shown.

00:59:27.000 --> 00:59:40.000
Secondly, that there was a concept of job relatedness came into being at that time. That it would be legal if it was job related.

00:59:40.000 --> 00:59:48.000
So if you tested an electrician on how do you set up a 220 volt socket, that would be a job related test.

00:59:48.000 --> 01:00:01.000
But that all evidence that could be obtained found that there was no job relatedness to this test.

01:00:01.000 --> 01:00:09.000
That you could not predict from the test how anybody would perform on the job in a paper mill.

01:00:09.000 --> 01:00:21.000
That's become common wisdom now. The EEOC ultimately issued guidelines on the issue and the office of contract compliance, the Department of Labor issued guidelines.

01:00:21.000 --> 01:00:38.000
Now employees are very sensitive about, very careful about using tests. But the result of them was that eight out of ten black employees were disqualified on the first half hour they were in the employment office.

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:56.000
And not so for whites. And the culture and then the science leads into cultural factors. One of the classic questions on the test, which I'll just use as an example, because it's such a good one, is what is RSVP me?

01:00:56.000 --> 01:01:10.000
Well, it turned out these black kids didn't know about RSVP. And that's a kind of symbolic question. But not isolated in its context, in its meaning.

01:01:10.000 --> 01:01:22.000
And that was something that was just bound to fall. And I did a lot of litigation in other cases in Washington, D.C., and elsewhere about these test things.

01:01:22.000 --> 01:01:30.000
Because there were different quirks that would come up. But the one-delict test was like a sitting duck because it had nothing to do with the work involved.

01:01:30.000 --> 01:01:50.000
Let me also ask you on the seniority side, you were due to briefly a few minutes ago to a very complicated question that you worked very, very hard to argue your way through. And that's the question of how does the law of grapple with the LAKIS CFX pre-act segregation, and so far as it reaches the seniority question?

01:01:50.000 --> 01:01:55.000
You want me to explain it about the problem?

01:01:55.000 --> 01:01:56.000
Yeah.

01:01:56.000 --> 01:02:11.000
Okay, I'll give you two examples. When Crowns Ella back merged the progression lines, which they did it voluntarily, you might say. They weren't a pressure from the EOC, but they did it early on.

01:02:11.000 --> 01:02:32.000
They couldn't maintain jobs with racial labels on them after the Civil Rights Act. They merged them by pay so that the white line may have been $3 an hour, $3.50, $4.55, and the black line would be $1.75, $2.50, $2.75.

01:02:32.000 --> 01:02:49.000
So they are making up those numbers, and they put them together. So at the result of putting them together based on their wage discrimination, they had all the black jobs at the bottom and the white jobs at the top, and they had a system of job seniority.

01:02:49.000 --> 01:02:58.000
It didn't matter how long you worked in the plant. The only thing that mattered was how long you worked in the next line down in the line of progression when there was a vacancy.

01:02:58.000 --> 01:03:06.000
So if there was a vacancy in the very top job, they'd look into the second top job, and they'd see who was in that second top job the longest.

01:03:06.000 --> 01:03:09.000
Well, you can see the ramifications of that.

01:03:09.000 --> 01:03:26.000
The only job any black man could enter was the lowest rating white job, and then he'd be the junior guy in that job, and they may have been 15 people in that job, and it would take 15 different promotions before he would be able to move into the next job.

01:03:26.000 --> 01:03:37.000
So the most basic thing we wanted and presented was that the seniority, the positions should be filled based on plant seniority.

01:03:37.000 --> 01:03:55.000
How long you worked for Crown Zellaback, so that when a job opened, and there were more than one people would sign a bid sheet to bid on the job, that the senior employee on a plant-wide basis would be given first consideration, and if he was qualified to do the job,

01:03:55.000 --> 01:04:07.000
he would get it. So that was very simple, and of course the defense had to do with qualifications, and how many years it would take to learn how to mix the glue, you know.

01:04:07.000 --> 01:04:19.000
So all these orders had reservations in them about qualifications, but they were carefully restricted to qualifications thing.

01:04:19.000 --> 01:04:45.000
And then came the notion of having to go through every job on the way to the top, which had always been the system, and they were all good, it's a non-racial system, we've always done this, you move from job 5 to 4 to 3, so that although a black employee on based on plants and yourity could go into the lowest ranking white job,

01:04:45.000 --> 01:05:05.000
he couldn't go into any other job without for serving in the lowest ranking job, and this is where the lawyers from the department of justice were really inspiring to me, I must say, that they should be allowed to go into any job that becomes open, as long as they can do the job.

01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:17.000
And so it wasn't just moving from jobs and yourity to plants and yourity, it was essentially eliminating the line of progression.

01:05:17.000 --> 01:05:34.000
That's a thumbnail of the basic points, and it would have different tricks and turns because the lines would sometimes go in two different directions halfway up, and you have to account for that somewhere other, but those were the two things, getting rid of plants and yourity and getting rid of the lines of progression.

01:05:34.000 --> 01:05:52.000
And they fought light hell about it, and the unions did as well initially, they turned around, but all it initially they did as well, because there was something sacred in the contract, the fact defenses were raised early on in Title VII, that if it's in the collective bottom agreement it can't be illegal.

01:05:52.000 --> 01:06:01.000
And so that was another hurdle you had to overcome, the contract was illegal itself, and so those were the kinds of issues that were involved.

01:06:01.000 --> 01:06:19.000
You and your civil road would become an absolutely critical piece in our Law Review, published 69 on these questions, and would have so much influence on how courts grapple with these things, including through Creeps and et cetera.

01:06:19.000 --> 01:06:26.000
And I'm very interested in your perspective on both how you labor to construct that piece.

01:06:26.000 --> 01:06:40.000
And the challenges you found in front of you in crafting the arguments that had been once you've been working on, obviously, in the fact of litigation, and your sense of the impact of that piece.

01:06:40.000 --> 01:06:48.000
I want to go back and give you my second example on the preceding question, because it's going to feed into what you're saying.

01:06:48.000 --> 01:06:56.000
Another situation was where no blacks were hired at all, and that was true in the New Orleans transit system.

01:06:56.000 --> 01:07:00.000
Every bus driver, every trolley driver in town was white.

01:07:00.000 --> 01:07:11.000
And when the Civil Rights Act passed, they began to hire black employees, and they had a system of company whites and yority.

01:07:11.000 --> 01:07:16.000
The one we were fighting for in Buggles, they already had it, but the black employees didn't have it.

01:07:16.000 --> 01:07:26.000
And as a result, they would get all the Saturday night shifts and overtime and late at night, and not the good jobs.

01:07:26.000 --> 01:07:40.000
And we had a case against New Orleans Public Service, the Fagan against Nopsy, in which also before Judge Hevy, in which he required the assignment of the law.

01:07:40.000 --> 01:07:50.000
He required the assignment of job assignments by random, by lottery.

01:07:50.000 --> 01:07:54.000
That was a completely different remedy, because they all could drive the bus.

01:07:54.000 --> 01:07:57.000
It's just a question at which bus, what time of day you're driving the bus.

01:07:57.000 --> 01:08:06.000
So it had to do with the situation where the vestige of past discrimination is not a segregated system like in Bougalooza, but no black employees at all.

01:08:06.000 --> 01:08:09.000
And what happens when you get in?

01:08:09.000 --> 01:08:12.000
Okay.

01:08:12.000 --> 01:08:15.000
The article.

01:08:15.000 --> 01:08:28.000
This theory, I don't want to get too technical on you, but there's a provision in Title VII that protects non-discriminatory seniority systems.

01:08:29.000 --> 01:08:35.000
And the people defending the status quo would always say, has to be non-discriminatory.

01:08:35.000 --> 01:08:39.000
It was created before. There was any black competition for these jobs.

01:08:39.000 --> 01:08:44.000
Our position was it was discriminatory because of the impact it had on the black employees.

01:08:44.000 --> 01:08:54.000
And the position that we argued soon became widely accepted in the intermediate federal courts.

01:08:55.000 --> 01:09:02.000
And the article that we wrote, I think, contributed to that.

01:09:02.000 --> 01:09:09.000
Although I must say it was well underway by 1916, but I think it contributed to that.

01:09:09.000 --> 01:09:21.000
The way we wrote it was a little more scholarly than the briefs, so the arguments had caught, but essentially was along the same lines.

01:09:21.000 --> 01:09:25.000
George and I were all friends. It wasn't like we were strangers, came together for this.

01:09:25.000 --> 01:09:30.000
We had tried hicks together. But before that, we were friends in Washington when I was working.

01:09:30.000 --> 01:09:36.000
He was a Covenant Burling, and I was an Arnold Porter, and we were lived in the same neighborhood and we were friends.

01:09:36.000 --> 01:09:39.000
And he came down here because I asked him to, and that kind of thing.

01:09:39.000 --> 01:09:45.000
So it was a very more than collegial. We're all friends writing this thing.

01:09:45.000 --> 01:09:50.000
And I wrote half. He wrote half. He edited my half. I edited his half.

01:09:50.000 --> 01:09:55.000
And we sent it to the Harvard Law Review. They edited the whole thing. They rearranged it completely.

01:09:55.000 --> 01:10:00.000
They put the end at the beginning. And it's how I published.

01:10:00.000 --> 01:10:06.000
But it came out at a key time, and it was in the Harvard Law Review, and a lot of people read it.

01:10:06.000 --> 01:10:16.000
George once told me that he had gotten a notification from some group that it was the most cited Law Review article in many years.

01:10:16.000 --> 01:10:26.000
But Supreme Court had yet to be heard from. And to make a long story short, when it got to Supreme Court, they ruled with what the employer's position on this.

01:10:26.000 --> 01:10:36.000
That the system was not discriminatory. If it wasn't adopted with a purpose of injuring or just hampering black minority employment,

01:10:36.000 --> 01:10:46.000
in a case involving, I think, the United States versus Teamsters in 1976, maybe 75.

01:10:46.000 --> 01:10:55.000
So we had a good run because from 1967 until 1965 or 66,

01:10:55.000 --> 01:11:07.000
I'm sorry, 1967 until 1975 or 76, everybody was doing what we were advocating, including the Department of Labor and the contract compliance field.

01:11:07.000 --> 01:11:13.000
Are you familiar with that? So it was almost, the job was almost done.

01:11:13.000 --> 01:11:17.000
Supreme Court comes along and says, no, it should never happen.

01:11:17.000 --> 01:11:27.000
So that was a big kind of intellectual disappointment, but I do feel the job had been done in that instance.

01:11:27.000 --> 01:11:36.000
And I did feel that we contributed to that. One thing I want to say about it is when I went to Washington,

01:11:36.000 --> 01:11:47.000
see I worked in Michigan for one semester, I didn't want to stay as a professor, came to Washington and got back into civil rights through the Civil Rights, from the Washington Research Project.

01:11:47.000 --> 01:11:57.000
But then I went into private practice and what I was getting into finding ways to make money was representing unions.

01:11:57.000 --> 01:12:03.000
And one thing we developed was the right of a union to bring a title seven case.

01:12:03.000 --> 01:12:10.000
And I was working for unions and doing that, I'm scripting away ahead now.

01:12:10.000 --> 01:12:20.000
But the people who were the power, the power that be people in the Washington Union establishment still held it against me because of that article.

01:12:20.000 --> 01:12:31.000
And they were very resentful at first. And I had a lot of headwind about that in terms of becoming a lawyer for unions because I had done this kind of traitorous thing.

01:12:31.000 --> 01:12:36.000
That was the major personal manifestation that came out of it. And some people still feel that way about it.

01:12:36.000 --> 01:12:50.000
The point they were making is if you're being a lawyer, you should be a lawyer, you're going to be a scholarly, you should be a scholar, you shouldn't mix them because it pollutes the objectivity of the scholarly endeavor.

01:12:50.000 --> 01:13:00.000
And the truth is I wrote that article the same way I handled Civil Rights case. I wrote that article to advance Civil Rights. I wasn't really trying to be a scholar, although it reads that way.

01:13:00.000 --> 01:13:10.000
And so there was something, I guess, some merit in what they were saying. But that was an outgrowth for me, the guy who was the chief guy at the AFL-CIO for example, didn't want to hear about me.

01:13:10.000 --> 01:13:13.000
So...

01:13:14.000 --> 01:13:18.000
Can we pause again here just for a second?

01:13:18.000 --> 01:13:20.000
I...

01:13:20.000 --> 01:13:22.000
Okay.

01:13:22.000 --> 01:13:33.000
Continue to mention the importance of these judges in influencing these cases. And it seems to be that that was the case throughout the South as well.

01:13:33.000 --> 01:13:36.000
Throughout the country.

01:13:37.000 --> 01:13:52.000
Listen, this week, five Justice Supreme Court think it's cruel and unusual punishment to keep these prisoners in California, cooked up in these little boots, and four think it's not.

01:13:52.000 --> 01:14:04.000
Well, that just tells you the whole story. It's all how the judge feels. It's all law falls away when you get down to those kind of decisions. It's just how who's the person?

01:14:05.000 --> 01:14:14.000
And that happens every day all over the country constantly. And it happened here when...

01:14:14.000 --> 01:14:25.000
And it's happening now. You can't do a thing in Civil Rights and the courts in New Orleans, the federal courts right now. Every judge on that district court and the court of appeals, they're all bad.

01:14:25.000 --> 01:14:28.000
You're thinking of...

01:14:28.000 --> 01:14:31.000
Oh, I don't care at all.

01:14:31.000 --> 01:14:39.000
Anyway, maybe I'm wrong about every judge, but certainly you can't do the kind of things we were doing. Then they had open arms for us.

01:14:39.000 --> 01:14:49.000
I went to Judges' Houses on weekends. They welcomed you in. I spent July 4th, 1967 in Judge Kristen Berry's home in the French Quarter.

01:14:49.000 --> 01:14:58.000
And he was on the phone telling the people in Bogalusia. He didn't let those people out of jail in 20 minutes. He was going to have the US Marshal's Force up there and arrest them.

01:14:58.000 --> 01:15:10.000
Yeah, it was all that. And through a lot of times I felt I was just kind of setting the table so these guys could do what they felt they should do.

01:15:10.000 --> 01:15:19.000
And if you got the wrong thing like the guy in Baton Rouge, it was nothing you could tell them. You could cite cases all day long. They wouldn't care.

01:15:19.000 --> 01:15:28.000
I mean, I feel that very strongly. That's one of the reasons why I'm not that interested in law anymore.

01:15:28.000 --> 01:15:34.000
Because it's so obvious to me that what we're doing is just a little bit... It's kind of pill political, you might say.

01:15:34.000 --> 01:15:43.000
The title of seven cases that Richard Handle lasted for years. Mills Douglas started a case about the Kaiser aluminum plant.

01:15:43.000 --> 01:15:49.000
By the time that case was finished and it gone up through the acrylic quartz and through the Supreme Court.

01:15:49.000 --> 01:15:58.000
In fact, it was... Relief was handed down, which given out 17 years after they began.

01:15:58.000 --> 01:16:07.000
That's another problem. One of those cases lasted so long the plant closed down.

01:16:07.000 --> 01:16:14.000
But they still had to pay out millions of dollars for what they had done.

01:16:14.000 --> 01:16:25.000
Okay, let me turn your remember back to the very unusual episode in 1967 when I end up in jail and it involves Leander Perez.

01:16:25.000 --> 01:16:33.000
And I'm sure that that's enough to cue you for a very interesting story.

01:16:33.000 --> 01:16:50.000
Well, in the early 1967 January of February, Gary Duncan and I'm in him, Gary Duncan and his mother... Gary was 19 years old at the time. His mother came to my office.

01:16:50.000 --> 01:16:58.000
They had been sent there by the Civil Rights Division of the Department of Justice, which had an office in New Orleans. They had gone there for help.

01:16:58.000 --> 01:17:04.000
And they couldn't handle criminal cases, defend criminal cases, and they sent them to me.

01:17:04.000 --> 01:17:18.000
And what happened was this young man had a little bit background. Leander Perez fought like no one ever had before had fought against desegregating the public schools and the parish.

01:17:18.000 --> 01:17:42.000
Leander Perez was a well-known racist figure who espoused theories of interposition and secession and barring the schoolhouse door and he appeared before Congress and he said these things.

01:17:42.000 --> 01:17:56.000
He said at one point, if any civil rights activist ever comes to a document's parish, we have a special place for him on Prince Philip Island with the allocators.

01:17:56.000 --> 01:18:11.000
But no one had ever come down and no one had ever done that. In fact, the government brought the school desegregation case and the reason is that it was the only place in Louisiana that nobody would be the plaintiff would stand up and be the plaintiff because of the intimidation that this man had created.

01:18:11.000 --> 01:18:21.000
His son was a district attorney and he appointed the judges. He was the head of the parish council, which is the governing body down there.

01:18:21.000 --> 01:18:40.000
The older man was appointed the judges. So, Judge Kristen Berry heard the case, put an injunction and effect requiring certain desegregation.

01:18:40.000 --> 01:18:51.000
By that time, it was so things had passed to the point that he actually entered an order that achieved some desegregation on a more than token basis in Plakamins parish.

01:18:51.000 --> 01:19:09.000
And there's a lot of furor down there about this. And Duncan was driving his truck down the only highway there is on the west side of the Mississippi River in Plakamins parish and he came to the school and he saw that his two of his nephews were being encountered by four white boys on the side of the road.

01:19:09.000 --> 01:19:19.000
He could see a fight was developing. He got out of the truck. He asked that was going on and one of his cousins said they're giving us a problem and he said, well, get in the truck.

01:19:19.000 --> 01:19:27.000
And at this point, he's a very sweet guy, Duncan. He touched one of the boys on the elbow and said, go ahead on.

01:19:27.000 --> 01:19:37.000
Well, the father of one of the boys was within eyesight of this and he reported that Duncan had slapped his son.

01:19:37.000 --> 01:19:48.000
And that night, Duncan was arrested and charged with battery, criminal charge punishable by two years in jail.

01:19:48.000 --> 01:20:01.000
And God bless him. He wasn't going to accept that. And he, like I say, he and his mother went to the Department of Justice. They sent him to me.

01:20:01.000 --> 01:20:11.000
I agreed to represent him with Collins Douglass in Eli. We all agreed to represent him. And we began to represent him.

01:20:11.000 --> 01:20:23.000
And we represented, we didn't just raise civil rights issues in cases. When we were representing somebody, we represent, like any lawyer, raise every issue possibly could to help your client.

01:20:23.000 --> 01:20:35.000
One of them was the Louisiana jury system at the time, which did not allow for juries in any case, unless the punishment was more than two years.

01:20:35.000 --> 01:20:54.000
So he was going to be tried before this judge that Perez had appointed. So I filed a motion to challenge that system, whatever the motion was exactly called, but to question the constitutionality of the lack of jury trial was denied.

01:20:54.000 --> 01:21:10.000
We tried the case. I had my witnesses. They had their witnesses. The judge ruled for the, for the state and sentenced, not into prison, actually 60 days in prison and a fine.

01:21:10.000 --> 01:21:24.000
And I was intent on appealing, particularly on the jury issue, because the law on the Supreme Court was developing that more and more of the provisions of the Bill of Rights were going to be applicable and stay criminal proceedings.

01:21:24.000 --> 01:21:38.000
In fact, I mentioned before, a courtist had just won that for counsel, right to counsel. So I went to the Supreme Court of Louisiana. So I needed to go to the Supreme Court of Louisiana to exhaust my remedies and then apply rits to the Supreme Court.

01:21:38.000 --> 01:21:49.000
And I went down after the, so I did that. I got, I kept them at a jail until the Supreme Court of Louisiana acted on it.

01:21:49.000 --> 01:22:02.000
They issued a one sentence order saying no violation, then they recited what the statute said. And I went down again to get a state of execution of the sentence until I filed the petition of Supreme Court.

01:22:02.000 --> 01:22:15.000
And I went to the judge's office. I called the headmaid and appointed. I knew I was coming. I went down there. He signed the state. He kept on going out of jail until, and as I walked out, Leander Perez and a sheriff standing there in the hall arrested me.

01:22:15.000 --> 01:22:34.000
And the charge was practicing law without a license, which in fact, I didn't have a Louisiana license. I was a lawyer temporarily in the state, reacting with local counsel. That's my legal position.

01:22:34.000 --> 01:22:47.000
So they put me in jail. And I got one phone call and I made it to my colleagues in New Orleans and Don Juno came down and bailed me out before the afternoon was out.

01:22:47.000 --> 01:23:00.000
And I was in the jail with the white prisoners, and holding with the white prisoners. And some guys started telling me the story about another LCD lawyer. I knew it was an LCD story in Alabama, who had been arrested for the same reason.

01:23:00.000 --> 01:23:10.000
And they said, can you imagine anyone representing me? They got it. So, and I'm saying, oh, really? Really? Is that right?

01:23:10.000 --> 01:23:39.000
But Juno got me out. And we are consulted with my other people involved with my situation down there. And we filed a case to join my prosecution and to declare the any prohibition on the activities of outside civil rights lawyers, unconstitutional as a violated, not only the lawyers rights, but the individuals rights to counsel.

01:23:39.000 --> 01:23:59.000
And that became a, I got blown up. So the case was assigned to Judge Casabrey because of a constitutionality of a state law involved. A three-judge court was assembled, which included Judge Hebe, my friend. And Judge Ainsworth, a member of the Court of Appeals.

01:23:59.000 --> 01:24:11.000
And there was discovery, and then there was a trial in the trial lasted for three weeks. And every day there was a story in the Times per Kiyun about what was going on in the courtroom.

01:24:11.000 --> 01:24:25.000
And essentially, it took just a few minutes of an hour, so to describe what I just said to you, what the facts were. It all turned out to, like, a congressional committee hearing on the state of law practice in Louisiana.

01:24:25.000 --> 01:24:40.000
And lawyers were coming in from all over the state, both brought in, or the government intervened on our side. It was me and Duncan with the plaintiffs and the head of court, Isaac Reynolds at that time, with the plaintiffs.

01:24:40.000 --> 01:24:52.000
And then the government became a plaintiff intervener, and this defendant was Perez and the state of Louisiana intervened on the side of the Perez.

01:24:52.000 --> 01:25:05.000
And the State Bar Association intervened on the side of Perez. So there were five parties. And a small part of the testimony had to do with me and Duncan and what happened in Louisiana.

01:25:05.000 --> 01:25:18.000
90% had to do with how does a black person get a lawyer in this state if he wants to break certain rights under federal law? And it was very interesting to watch.

01:25:18.000 --> 01:25:36.000
And in due course, the federal court avoided the constitutional question, which is what courts are supposed to do. And they see there were two defenses. One is the constitution was to protect protecting what I was doing.

01:25:36.000 --> 01:25:47.000
Another is that Louisiana statute says an out of state lawyer can practice in cooperation with local counsel if he's temporarily in the state.

01:25:47.000 --> 01:25:59.000
So I was in my second year of residence here. But the fact is I was on leave from Audel and Porter. I had an arrangement with them. I could go back. And that was official that I was on leave.

01:25:59.000 --> 01:26:12.000
I was supposed to go stay here for one year. That was my first leave of absence was for one year. At the end of the first year, I had already been arrested. And the trial was coming up. It just didn't seem right to be leaving. Plus I was in the middle of the things that I didn't want to leave.

01:26:12.000 --> 01:26:27.000
And they gave me another year's leave of absence. So that was very helpful. And we tried it. And they were trying to prove I was a resident by the fact that I had utility bills. And I'm trying to prove I'm not. Because I still have a DC driver's license.

01:26:27.000 --> 01:26:38.000
That was going on. That was one part. And the other part was about the state of law in Louisiana. And they issued an opinion ruling on the part that I was temporarily in the state.

01:26:38.000 --> 01:26:49.000
And they said that I am temporary in the state. And I was leaving in August like he's like a testify. And that I was operating with local counsel. It was, I certainly was.

01:26:49.000 --> 01:27:09.000
Their names was on everything. And Bob Collins was there the first day. And I went down alone after the first day. But Bob Collins was there the first day. And there was a problem about federal courts issuing injunctions against state criminal proceedings, which is embodied in a federal statute. But that is an exception when the federal government is asking for the injunction.

01:27:09.000 --> 01:27:21.000
So the government intervening in my behalf proved to be very helpful as well. Because when in the opinion they explained how they could issue this injunction by pointing out the government had asked for it.

01:27:21.000 --> 01:27:31.000
And so then I all that during this period I filed the application of the Supreme Court for Ritz. It was granted.

01:27:31.000 --> 01:27:51.000
The argument was scheduled Gary Duncan and I and several others went up to Washington and I argue the case. And decision came down ruling that it's illegal to file a violates the 14th amendment not to allow juries and state trials except for the most minor crimes.

01:27:51.000 --> 01:28:03.000
And not including what he was charged with. And so when it got back they decided to they tried Duncan again and they have a jury.

01:28:03.000 --> 01:28:17.000
And we brought a case saying the only reason you could possibly try the mad at this point after all this was just intimidation and vengeance. And we filed a case called Duncan versus Perez.

01:28:17.000 --> 01:28:31.000
And it went before Judge Cassidy and he ruled in our favor and he should have nice opinions saying that it was it couldn't inculc- unbelievable any other reason would could underlie the reason this was a malicious prosecution.

01:28:31.000 --> 01:28:45.000
And they enjoy them from prosecuting the reproduci-duck and so it was kind of a trifect I guess in that sense. And that's the story of that case.

01:28:45.000 --> 01:28:49.000
And he asked about-

01:28:49.000 --> 01:29:05.000
And he grew and turned out to be an important leader in the parish on all kinds of other issues. He became the head of a he became a stripper and he was the head of the stripper's association and represented he became an important figure after that.

01:29:05.000 --> 01:29:13.000
And he's still my friend. He was and he moved out of the parish after the hurricane but he still lives right.

01:29:13.000 --> 01:29:17.000
And he asked about some of the other work that you didn't in Louisiana.

01:29:17.000 --> 01:29:27.000
I think there's some very interesting voting rights litigation that you pursued up in Madison, Paris.

01:29:27.000 --> 01:29:33.000
Were you one couple of rather exceptional individuals?

01:29:33.000 --> 01:29:47.000
After the Voting Rights Act was passed in these largely black parishes in upstate Louisiana there was a lot of voter registration.

01:29:47.000 --> 01:30:05.000
You probably know this but the act bypassed all the unpleasantness and hurdles of going down to the white registrar who hated you and they would appoint federal registrars and made it nice and simple to get the registration done.

01:30:05.000 --> 01:30:13.000
So the voting population became very substantially African-American.

01:30:13.000 --> 01:30:34.000
And the first instance in which we brought a case was that there was a man named Zoma White who was the head of the Madison parish voters league who was running for police chief against the white police chief in town.

01:30:34.000 --> 01:30:40.000
And he lost the election when Frisk was came by by about 10-15 votes.

01:30:40.000 --> 01:30:53.000
And we investigated and later found out that the clerk of court had gone to the white old age homes in the parish of which they were numerous.

01:30:53.000 --> 01:31:06.000
And got all these white people to vote for the gay brought them ballots to their bedside and got them to and goes without saying didn't go to any black old age homes.

01:31:06.000 --> 01:31:10.000
And he had collected something like 200 ballots that way.

01:31:10.000 --> 01:31:14.000
And we filed suit of the Voting Rights Act.

01:31:14.000 --> 01:31:21.000
He was heard by a judge named Dawkins in Monroe.

01:31:21.000 --> 01:31:28.000
I believe the government intervened on our side in that case, the federal government, but maybe it was the next case.

01:31:28.000 --> 01:31:33.000
I don't really remember. No way second now. That was the second one.

01:31:33.000 --> 01:31:38.000
Trying to get this straight. One of them they did. One of them they didn't, I think.

01:31:38.000 --> 01:31:46.000
Anyway, the judge didn't want to cast any aspersions on the public officials.

01:31:46.000 --> 01:31:51.000
So he adopted a novel doctrine called discrimination in fact.

01:31:51.000 --> 01:31:55.000
He said they didn't mean anything bad, but in fact it was discriminatory.

01:31:55.000 --> 01:31:59.000
And he set aside the election and the election was held.

01:31:59.000 --> 01:32:03.000
White swung the election was police chief for many years.

01:32:03.000 --> 01:32:06.000
Did you advance that doctrine in your claim?

01:32:06.000 --> 01:32:11.000
The fact that he made that up. No, I didn't advance that doctrine.

01:32:11.000 --> 01:32:19.000
I went to the homes, white homes with these ballots. I know I can possibly say that, but I didn't care.

01:32:19.000 --> 01:32:25.000
And then the only way I ever knew who did that doctrine again was the same judge in the next case.

01:32:25.000 --> 01:32:33.000
The next case was a vacancy in the...

01:32:33.000 --> 01:32:38.000
Let me get this straight. Which position it was.

01:32:38.000 --> 01:32:44.000
I think it was a school board position.

01:32:44.000 --> 01:32:49.000
There was a vacancy and there had a fill in unexpired term.

01:32:49.000 --> 01:33:00.000
Now in Louisiana, there's a lever you can pull, at least there was then, to vote for everybody on the party line.

01:33:00.000 --> 01:33:04.000
And the symbol of the Democrats at that point was the rooster.

01:33:04.000 --> 01:33:11.000
And you could pull this tab in the voting booth and you'd be voting for everybody who's running as a rooster.

01:33:11.000 --> 01:33:20.000
And so there was a black candidate, a man named Harrison Brown, who was running for the school board.

01:33:20.000 --> 01:33:22.000
He was a teacher in the school system.

01:33:22.000 --> 01:33:30.000
And they disconnected that position from the line.

01:33:30.000 --> 01:33:37.000
So if you pulled that lever, you voted for everybody except Harrison Brown, who's on the line.

01:33:37.000 --> 01:33:48.000
And as a result, most people, most of the supporters didn't know that.

01:33:48.000 --> 01:33:53.000
I don't know how that worked for the White candidate, but it didn't adversely affect the White candidate for some reason or other.

01:33:53.000 --> 01:33:55.000
I mean, I do it the way the ballot was set up.

01:33:55.000 --> 01:34:00.000
So all his supporters went down. All the voters, league members, went down to vote for him.

01:34:00.000 --> 01:34:03.000
And they think they're voting for him. They walked out and they hadn't voted for him.

01:34:03.000 --> 01:34:06.000
So the other guy wins by a tremendous amount.

01:34:06.000 --> 01:34:10.000
Well, same story. We filed a case.

01:34:10.000 --> 01:34:14.000
That's the one I think the government intervened on.

01:34:14.000 --> 01:34:18.000
And the judge found after with a lengthy trial and all that stuff.

01:34:18.000 --> 01:34:22.000
And the judge found that there's another instance of discrimination.

01:34:22.000 --> 01:34:24.000
In fact, they didn't mean it.

01:34:24.000 --> 01:34:27.000
And he called, he required that election to be held again.

01:34:27.000 --> 01:34:30.000
And it was held again. And Harrison Brown won.

01:34:30.000 --> 01:34:35.000
And was a member of the school board.

01:34:35.000 --> 01:34:39.000
And that stopped happening up there. That was the end of that.

01:34:39.000 --> 01:34:42.000
The elections were right after that.

01:34:42.000 --> 01:34:53.000
And I think democracy had it played its will there as a result of the demographics.

01:34:53.000 --> 01:35:02.000
I feel so represented Robert Hicks in a, when he came to you in concerning the pending instructions

01:35:02.000 --> 01:35:04.000
in public housing, Bogolusa.

01:35:04.000 --> 01:35:05.000
Yes.

01:35:05.000 --> 01:35:07.000
And the concerns that you were able to find.

01:35:07.000 --> 01:35:09.000
Yes.

01:35:09.000 --> 01:35:15.000
Hicks was following the plans for the construction of government public housing in Bogolusa.

01:35:15.000 --> 01:35:22.000
And realized that by the placement of housing, they were placing the housing deep into black neighborhoods

01:35:22.000 --> 01:35:29.000
and deep into white neighborhoods and none along the areas that might be considered mixed.

01:35:29.000 --> 01:35:32.000
And he wanted to know whether he could stop it.

01:35:32.000 --> 01:35:37.000
And we researched it and decided that it was a violation.

01:35:37.000 --> 01:35:48.000
It could be said to be a violation of the non-discrimination provisions of a recently enacted news, a new civil rights act that had been enacted by then.

01:35:48.000 --> 01:35:58.000
And I think this is 1967. There was another one, little vague on, I think this fair housing law was a separate law from the civil rights law and the voting rights law.

01:35:58.000 --> 01:36:00.000
My memory serves me, is that right?

01:36:00.000 --> 01:36:04.000
And we brought the suit under that.

01:36:04.000 --> 01:36:09.000
It had never been established that any private person could sue under that.

01:36:09.000 --> 01:36:13.000
Or that the relief we were seeking was plausible. It was available.

01:36:13.000 --> 01:36:20.000
And we litigated that case against the federal government who had helped us in all these other cases.

01:36:20.000 --> 01:36:26.000
I'm suing HUD and they're bringing representatives by the Department of Justice, probably by the Civil Rights Division.

01:36:26.000 --> 01:36:36.000
And Judge Casabray found we did have a right of action and that we, it was discriminatory to do that and he enjoyed the construction of the housing.

01:36:36.000 --> 01:36:46.000
At the last minute they had the bulldozers in ready to clear the land and the word came up from New York to Bogalosa, the judges issued an order of turn-off those bulldozers.

01:36:46.000 --> 01:36:53.000
And they couldn't build them that way and they built them the other way as far as I remember I think they did or maybe they abandoned it.

01:36:53.000 --> 01:36:56.000
I'm not really sure about that point but they weren't allowed to do that.

01:36:56.000 --> 01:37:06.000
And I mentioned that to you as an example of creativity that Hicks would have in spotting every aspect of what he was trying to prevent.

01:37:06.000 --> 01:37:15.000
And I think we talked earlier about some of the treatment of the football players and the cheerleaders and the...

01:37:15.000 --> 01:37:16.000
The Pram.

01:37:16.000 --> 01:37:20.000
The Pram, same kind of thing with the football players, they wouldn't let...

01:37:20.000 --> 01:37:27.000
First they wouldn't let them on the football team and they wouldn't play them and they would only play in positions that they didn't want to play in.

01:37:27.000 --> 01:37:34.000
We got Judge Hebe into every little detail about who's gonna... like he was the coach of the football team.

01:37:34.000 --> 01:37:51.000
And all that was from Robert Hicks and he wasn't gonna take half a loaf and that's one of the fantastic things about the man really is that he wasn't gonna settle for part of it.

01:37:51.000 --> 01:37:53.000
So, I suppose.

01:37:54.000 --> 01:37:56.000
The case of Hicks against Weaver.

01:37:56.000 --> 01:37:57.000
Hicks against Weaver.

01:37:59.000 --> 01:38:00.000
69.

01:38:00.000 --> 01:38:01.000
Yeah.

01:38:01.000 --> 01:38:02.000
District Courtroom.

01:38:02.000 --> 01:38:03.000
Yeah.

01:38:03.000 --> 01:38:11.000
One of the things about welfare cases and also a case involving sweet potatoes down.

01:38:11.000 --> 01:38:12.000
Okay.

01:38:15.000 --> 01:38:17.000
The welfare cases.

01:38:18.000 --> 01:38:38.000
Annie and I, my wife Annie and I and Lola C. Light became involved in representing a group of women who were being criminally prosecuted in federal court New Orleans under for charges of welfare fraud, receiving more welfare than they were entitled, welfare payments than they were entitled to.

01:38:38.000 --> 01:38:40.000
And we...

01:38:43.000 --> 01:38:48.000
We tried two of those cases on the facts before juries.

01:38:48.000 --> 01:38:52.000
I'm gonna tell you the result first and then what happened along the way.

01:38:52.000 --> 01:39:05.000
And of the 20-something women involved, one who had some prior criminal record served three months in prison in West Virginia.

01:39:05.000 --> 01:39:07.000
And all the others didn't have any...

01:39:07.000 --> 01:39:08.000
Any...

01:39:08.000 --> 01:39:10.000
So it was rather successful.

01:39:10.000 --> 01:39:11.000
I think it was kind of...

01:39:11.000 --> 01:39:14.000
There was a plea bog in there at the end about...

01:39:14.000 --> 01:39:18.000
After a lot of other litigation, I'm about to describe where they would...

01:39:18.000 --> 01:39:26.000
Drop the other cases, this one woman who had this record would serve three months and know where the end of it.

01:39:26.000 --> 01:39:37.000
But in the meantime, we dug into it and firstly we challenged the composition of the grand jury, the racial and economic composition of the jury that had issued these indictments.

01:39:40.000 --> 01:39:44.000
Because these were very petty offenses that they were being charged with.

01:39:44.000 --> 01:39:50.000
And did some computer work that enabled us to...

01:39:51.000 --> 01:39:58.000
The race of the jurors was shown in the court records, but the relative poverty, non-poverty was not.

01:39:58.000 --> 01:40:03.000
And we were able to get a hold of the food stamp, computer tapes.

01:40:03.000 --> 01:40:06.000
These are the days of computer tapes.

01:40:06.000 --> 01:40:08.000
And the voting roll tapes.

01:40:08.000 --> 01:40:15.000
And have a computer determine what percentage of the people on the food stamp list were registered voters.

01:40:15.000 --> 01:40:22.000
And it turned out that 30% of the food stamp recipients were registered to vote.

01:40:22.000 --> 01:40:26.000
And 78% of all other people were registered to vote.

01:40:26.000 --> 01:40:34.000
And that meant that there was not a fair cross-section of the community in the jury pool.

01:40:34.000 --> 01:40:44.000
The authorities that be wiggled around that by reducing the figures down to a particular grand jury of seven people.

01:40:44.000 --> 01:40:51.000
And the grand jury of 17 and deciding it would only make the difference of 1.4 persons per jury.

01:40:51.000 --> 01:40:58.000
In other words, instead of a representation of one statistically, it would be 2.4.

01:40:58.000 --> 01:41:04.000
That difference was not substantial.

01:41:04.000 --> 01:41:07.000
That's the decision then.

01:41:07.000 --> 01:41:12.000
Golf first of the United States, I cited that.

01:41:12.000 --> 01:41:17.000
Which is pretty tricky in my mind, actually.

01:41:17.000 --> 01:41:24.000
It had never been established at that time that there was an economic component to a fair cross-section.

01:41:24.000 --> 01:41:27.000
But since it has been, but they didn't rule that there wasn't.

01:41:27.000 --> 01:41:34.000
They just ruled that there wasn't enough, which, let me just say I disagree with.

01:41:34.000 --> 01:41:42.000
Then when they went to the first trial, the prosecutor used his prectery challenges to eliminate every black person in the panel.

01:41:42.000 --> 01:41:47.000
So that the only people who could be on the jury were white. And the jury was all white.

01:41:47.000 --> 01:41:53.000
And we challenged the legality of the use of prectery challenges in that way.

01:41:53.000 --> 01:42:02.000
And there was no law on that because prectery challenges had always been defined as a lawyer can get rid of anybody who wants to, doesn't have to have a reason.

01:42:02.000 --> 01:42:10.000
And we convinced Judge Rubin, the trial judge, that he could be any reason they want except race.

01:42:10.000 --> 01:42:17.000
And that this, the fact that he eliminated every black juror, was proof that it was race.

01:42:17.000 --> 01:42:23.000
And he held that. And that's the reported decision called the United States versus McDaniels.

01:42:23.000 --> 01:42:29.000
And I believe that hadn't happened before. I'm not sure of that.

01:42:29.000 --> 01:42:36.000
But I know this that 20 years later, Supreme Court adopted that as a rule of national applicability in a case called Batson.

01:42:36.000 --> 01:42:45.000
Where now, when a prosecutor in federal courts all over the country, if a prosecutor is disproportionate,

01:42:45.000 --> 01:42:55.000
disproportionately removes black jurors, he has to submit in writing to the judge reasonable, non-racial reasons for that.

01:42:55.000 --> 01:43:06.000
And as a result, prosecutors don't do it. So it was a, Vance the Bull in that way.

01:43:06.000 --> 01:43:20.000
And I think we did okay by our clients because what I said, when they first were charged, they were all fearful of spending years in jail and they didn't have to.

01:43:21.000 --> 01:43:25.000
That was after LCDC. See, I came back to Louisiana later on.

01:43:25.000 --> 01:43:26.000
And, yeah.

01:43:26.000 --> 01:43:37.000
Can you just carefully do the chronology, the basic chronology mid, say 67 forward from the end or for as good forward?

01:43:37.000 --> 01:43:45.000
I stayed in Louisiana as employed by LCDC until, I stayed in Louisiana till August 1968.

01:43:46.000 --> 01:43:50.000
I was employed by LCDC until December 1968.

01:43:50.000 --> 01:43:55.000
I went to Washington where I had come from. I did not want to go back to Arnold and Porter.

01:43:55.000 --> 01:43:59.000
I was, you can imagine, was a changed person at this point.

01:43:59.000 --> 01:44:09.000
And I wrote, I worked at the, I had an office at the Institute for Policy Studies and I wrote my part of the article with George.

01:44:10.000 --> 01:44:14.000
And in the meantime, I had been offered a position teaching in the University of Michigan.

01:44:14.000 --> 01:44:19.000
And in, at the first of the year, moved out to Michigan.

01:44:19.000 --> 01:44:23.000
I did, I didn't like January 69.

01:44:23.000 --> 01:44:24.000
January 69.

01:44:27.000 --> 01:44:29.000
Did not enjoy teaching.

01:44:29.000 --> 01:44:33.000
And in addition to that, I was running the Louisiana all the time.

01:44:34.000 --> 01:44:38.000
These cases I was handling, I never stopped in them until they were over.

01:44:38.000 --> 01:44:42.000
And whatever in condition I was in, I was still doing these cases.

01:44:42.000 --> 01:44:48.000
So I had a schedule of teaching Thursday and Friday, which is pretty sweet, really.

01:44:48.000 --> 01:44:52.000
But I would leave Saturday morning and come back Wednesday night.

01:44:52.000 --> 01:44:55.000
And I was in Louisiana at the LCDC office the whole time.

01:44:55.000 --> 01:44:57.000
So I didn't really give it a fair chance.

01:44:57.000 --> 01:45:02.000
And the woman I was married to at that time didn't like living in Annover.

01:45:03.000 --> 01:45:09.000
So after one semester, I left and I went to work for Marion Edelman, Marion Wright Edelman at the,

01:45:09.000 --> 01:45:12.000
what was then called the Washington Research Project.

01:45:12.000 --> 01:45:15.000
And I, it wasn't then focused the way it is now.

01:45:15.000 --> 01:45:17.000
Now it's called the Children's Defense Fund.

01:45:17.000 --> 01:45:19.000
And now it's all about children.

01:45:19.000 --> 01:45:22.000
But at that time, that hadn't been clarified in her mind.

01:45:22.000 --> 01:45:29.000
And we were going to bring cases that would push the government in the right direction on civil rights.

01:45:29.000 --> 01:45:34.000
And I did that for two years with a lot of help.

01:45:34.000 --> 01:45:36.000
There was staff there.

01:45:36.000 --> 01:45:38.000
There were people there.

01:45:38.000 --> 01:45:41.000
It was much different.

01:45:41.000 --> 01:45:45.000
And I mentioned a few of the cases in the memo I gave you.

01:45:45.000 --> 01:45:53.000
And in 1971, I decided I would want it to be back in Louisiana.

01:45:53.000 --> 01:46:04.000
And I moved back and that's, and soon thereafter, well, there was a divorce and are involved here.

01:46:04.000 --> 01:46:07.000
And Ann and I came to live with me here.

01:46:07.000 --> 01:46:11.000
And that's when we got into this welfare litigation.

01:46:11.000 --> 01:46:14.000
And other cases, other cases.

01:46:14.000 --> 01:46:20.000
The case against Nopsey about the bus drivers was in that period and so forth.

01:46:20.000 --> 01:46:29.000
And then several years later in 1974, the idea of my children being in Washington and me being here kind of caught up with me.

01:46:29.000 --> 01:46:32.000
And we moved back to Washington.

01:46:32.000 --> 01:46:36.000
I lived there for 17 years.

01:46:36.000 --> 01:46:41.000
I worked for Marion again for a while.

01:46:41.000 --> 01:46:49.000
And then one of the other people in that office, Mike Tristan, I opened a law firm on our own.

01:46:49.000 --> 01:46:55.000
And practice together, so will interest her.

01:46:55.000 --> 01:46:58.000
Thank you for that.

01:46:58.000 --> 01:47:02.000
Two last things and then we'll break the internship with any last thing that you might have.

01:47:02.000 --> 01:47:08.000
I want to, even mentioned earlier, I want to make sure we talk about there was a very interesting case involving the cooperative in South Sweet Potatoes.

01:47:08.000 --> 01:47:14.000
Okay.

01:47:14.000 --> 01:47:21.000
The case arose out of the area of Upper Lucis, Louisiana and,

01:47:21.000 --> 01:47:25.000
name of that town again.

01:47:25.000 --> 01:47:27.000
Was Stanley lives?

01:47:27.000 --> 01:47:32.000
Lafayette, Louisiana, where there is a lot of sweet potato growing.

01:47:32.000 --> 01:47:35.000
Many of the farmers are black farmers.

01:47:35.000 --> 01:47:40.000
And for years, they had been selling the potatoes to a white host sailor.

01:47:40.000 --> 01:47:47.000
And much, much of the profit along the line of the potato reaching the table went to the host sailor and not to the farmer.

01:47:47.000 --> 01:47:53.000
And a group of people, one of whom was a core representative in that area, John Zippert,

01:47:53.000 --> 01:48:04.000
and a Catholic priest who had been assigned to a parish in that district name of Alfred McKnight, Albert McKnight.

01:48:04.000 --> 01:48:13.000
And many of the local farmers formed a, a farm's cooperative to process package and sell the sweet potatoes.

01:48:13.000 --> 01:48:24.000
And it became a quite resented by the powers, the white power structure, because there wasn't just one white host sailor.

01:48:24.000 --> 01:48:27.000
There were several and they were all being adversely hurt by this.

01:48:27.000 --> 01:48:42.000
And so the DA began to hassle them about their organization and call people before grand juries and all kinds of inappropriate things.

01:48:42.000 --> 01:48:53.000
And one night, he had his people, had the police break into their office and take away their files.

01:48:53.000 --> 01:48:57.000
And potentially trying to put them out of business.

01:48:57.000 --> 01:49:03.000
And the case came to us.

01:49:03.000 --> 01:49:17.000
And we sued in federal court in Lafayette to, I guess you'd say prohibit, to join the conduct and to return the documents.

01:49:17.000 --> 01:49:22.000
And the district attorney had to come in to federal court and explain what he was doing.

01:49:22.000 --> 01:49:24.000
And he was unable to do that.

01:49:24.000 --> 01:49:34.000
And the judges shoot an injunction prohibiting them from having any contact with this organization.

01:49:34.000 --> 01:49:36.000
And the organization is still there.

01:49:36.000 --> 01:49:45.000
It's called the Southern consumers.

01:49:45.000 --> 01:49:46.000
I forgot the name.

01:49:46.000 --> 01:49:48.000
So it's got the other word, Southern consumers cooperative.

01:49:48.000 --> 01:49:50.000
And there's one more word in it.

01:49:50.000 --> 01:49:53.000
But it's, and the word's not potato.

01:49:53.000 --> 01:49:55.000
It's some other word.

01:49:55.000 --> 01:49:58.000
But anyway, it's something there.

01:49:58.000 --> 01:50:00.000
And they're still doing it.

01:50:00.000 --> 01:50:03.000
They're still handling their own host sailing.

01:50:03.000 --> 01:50:05.000
And so that was just a thing.

01:50:05.000 --> 01:50:06.000
It got me over to Lafayette.

01:50:06.000 --> 01:50:07.000
I'd never been there before.

01:50:07.000 --> 01:50:10.000
I didn't, we didn't have activity in Lafayette.

01:50:10.000 --> 01:50:15.000
And got to see what was going on there.

01:50:15.000 --> 01:50:20.000
And as a result, got to be friends with John Siprit, who was the core worker there.

01:50:20.000 --> 01:50:28.000
A white man who was wanting to marry one of the young ladies he had met out there named Carol Prasion.

01:50:28.000 --> 01:50:36.000
And the clerk of court wouldn't give him a marriage license, because there was mixed race.

01:50:36.000 --> 01:50:39.000
And the Supreme Court had just decided loving against Virginia.

01:50:39.000 --> 01:50:44.000
I walled in there with my suit to join me to require the

01:50:44.000 --> 01:50:46.000
clerk of court to give him a marriage license.

01:50:46.000 --> 01:50:47.000
And of course, he did.

01:50:47.000 --> 01:50:48.000
I got to go to the wedding.

01:50:48.000 --> 01:50:52.000
It was a happy occasion all around.

01:50:52.000 --> 01:50:55.000
Well, last thing, you mentioned that we should stop.

01:50:55.000 --> 01:50:59.000
Let's know if you can get immediate.

01:50:59.000 --> 01:51:02.000
I feel out of respect for all that you accomplished.

01:51:02.000 --> 01:51:07.000
It's really nice to have some of this more extensive records set down.

01:51:07.000 --> 01:51:13.000
So even if we're touching that in modest ways, the scope of it is another way to make the fun of the civil.

01:51:13.000 --> 01:51:17.000
And another angle of perspective maybe.

01:51:17.000 --> 01:51:19.000
And we're going there.

01:51:19.000 --> 01:51:21.000
My final question.

01:51:21.000 --> 01:51:25.000
You mentioned, and thank you for all your patience.

01:51:25.000 --> 01:51:27.000
You were very long in the room.

01:51:27.000 --> 01:51:31.000
You mentioned one point that, you know, on return to when you moved away from Louis Vuitton.

01:51:31.000 --> 01:51:36.000
In the late 60s that you kind of left to change person.

01:51:36.000 --> 01:51:39.000
And maybe just some reflections on yourself.

01:51:39.000 --> 01:51:41.000
Others you saw.

01:51:41.000 --> 01:51:46.000
Move through these very.

01:51:46.000 --> 01:51:50.000
To mulch you us and involving years on this issue.

01:51:50.000 --> 01:51:54.000
And your perspective on how that did change you and the things that.

01:51:54.000 --> 01:51:56.000
How you added the world differently.

01:51:56.000 --> 01:52:00.000
Okay.

01:52:00.000 --> 01:52:05.000
Let me say first something which I kind of passed over at the beginning.

01:52:05.000 --> 01:52:12.000
I mentioned that I didn't think these volunteer lawyers were earning their keep in terms of the cost to send them.

01:52:12.000 --> 01:52:17.000
But one thing which is undeniable is after being here for two or three or four weeks,

01:52:17.000 --> 01:52:20.000
they go back home and it would change their lives.

01:52:20.000 --> 01:52:29.000
And I, to this day, I'm hearing stories about lawyers who spent a short period of time either here or in Jackson or in Alabama.

01:52:29.000 --> 01:52:36.000
And they are the head of the Human Rights Commission in Pittsburgh or Cincinnati or something of that sort.

01:52:36.000 --> 01:52:42.000
And it really was like a contagion.

01:52:42.000 --> 01:52:44.000
I got a very big dose.

01:52:44.000 --> 01:52:48.000
But even for those smaller doses it was like a contagion and it's remarkable.

01:52:48.000 --> 01:52:52.000
And this is true of the law students as well who would come down.

01:52:52.000 --> 01:52:55.000
There was a group called law students civil committee for civil rights.

01:52:55.000 --> 01:52:57.000
It was a listric.

01:52:57.000 --> 01:53:05.000
And the law students were also changed and went into public service work or pro bono work.

01:53:05.000 --> 01:53:09.000
So I just wanted to mention that because what you said.

01:53:09.000 --> 01:53:18.000
I had been through all these experiences and not just legal but social.

01:53:18.000 --> 01:53:23.000
And we haven't mentioned the Vietnam War but that was coming.

01:53:23.000 --> 01:53:33.000
That was going on and I was meeting and spending time with anti-war activists and felt strongly about that too.

01:53:33.000 --> 01:53:44.000
And I got to the point that I could just see that there was what I was interested in.

01:53:44.000 --> 01:53:54.000
And I couldn't just see going back to a firm and being slaughtered into some anti-trust case representing one big corporation against another.

01:53:54.000 --> 01:54:07.000
It just, by the time the two years was over I just knew I was going to do work in this area.

01:54:07.000 --> 01:54:12.000
Not some other, you know, not a commercial area.

01:54:12.000 --> 01:54:17.000
And I was very lucky to be able to do that actually.

01:54:17.000 --> 01:54:21.000
Not only do it but do it on my own terms and my own law firm.

01:54:21.000 --> 01:54:28.000
And the reason were these two union lawyers I mentioned to you before made it possible because they really got me into having a billing client.

01:54:28.000 --> 01:54:30.000
All this stuff I've ever done in Louisiana.

01:54:30.000 --> 01:54:38.000
And there's never, no one's ever paid anything for it except if you win a title seven case the court makes the defendant pay you which is nice.

01:54:38.000 --> 01:54:43.000
But in terms of sustaining a law practice that's not a very good way to go about it.

01:54:43.000 --> 01:54:50.000
So I felt I wanted to do that and I feel I was very lucky to be able to do that.

01:54:50.000 --> 01:54:54.000
I don't know what else to say about it. It's just your mind is different.

01:54:54.000 --> 01:55:06.000
When I left Donald and Porter I wanted that leave of absence. I wanted that security that I could come back and I wasn't going to be floating out there without a job.

01:55:06.000 --> 01:55:11.000
And then by the first year was up I was kind of not so concerned about it although they extended it.

01:55:11.000 --> 01:55:14.000
At the end of the second year it was just completely out of the question.

01:55:14.000 --> 01:55:16.000
I had argued in the Supreme Court.

01:55:16.000 --> 01:55:18.000
These are these young lawyers.

01:55:18.000 --> 01:55:21.000
These big firms they go their whole lives and they're wrong.

01:55:21.000 --> 01:55:24.000
They're going to scream, go on and win.

01:55:24.000 --> 01:55:34.000
So it just was just expanded by it and was able to pursue it.

01:55:34.000 --> 01:55:36.000
Thank you.

01:55:36.000 --> 01:55:39.000
Thank you.

